// Jurassic Left Behind — full chapter data (auto-extracted)
window.NOVEL_CH = {
  1: {"n": 1, "title": "Chapter 1: The Man in the Cage", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A storm-dark 1993 InGen raptor transfer yard at night, floodlights cutting through rain, ex-military handlers around a steel transport crate, chain-link shadows across wet concrete, a dropped work glove near the cage track."}, "{{Jophery Brown}} had both hands on the gate when the crate moved.", "The rain had been falling for twenty minutes. It came down hard enough to turn the concrete apron outside the holding pen into black glass, hard enough that the floodlights made white rods out of the water. Men in rain ponchos stood around the transport crate with tasers and rifles and plastic face shields. The plastic shields were already fogged. The rifles were already wet.", "No one said the animal's name.", "They said <i>asset</i>. They said <i>female</i>. They said <i>the new one</i>. They said <i>keep the line tight</i>. They said <i>do not give her the corner</i>. The words were short, military, clipped. They moved from man to man as if a person could pass courage by radio.", "Jophery Brown was not new. Jophery Brown had worked four transfers and two feedings and one bad sedative recovery in the quarantine pens. He knew where to put his boots. He knew to keep his elbow out of the bite gap. He knew not to look into the dark inside the crate too long.", "That night, the dark looked back.", "The transport crate struck the rail stop with a metal sound that cut through the storm. The rear gate dropped. The {{raptor}} hit the inner mesh before the handlers had finished shouting.", "The first strike bent the mesh.", "The second strike moved the crate.", "The third strike moved every man around it.", "\"Hold it!\" {{Robert Muldoon}} shouted.", "The handler on Jophery Brown's right slipped. His shoulder struck Jophery Brown's shoulder. Jophery Brown's left hand lost the wet bar for one second, not even a full second, just the amount of time it took a boot sole to slide on concrete.", "The raptor took that second.", "There was no roar at first. There was a shriek, high and close, like metal torn under pressure. The crate lurched back from the gate. Jophery Brown's arm went into the gap up to the shoulder, and then the rest of him followed the arm.", "Men grabbed his belt. Men grabbed his boots. Men shouted his name and then stopped using his name because names did not help.", "Jophery Brown saw the floodlight once, sideways. He saw rain on the rifle barrel above him. He saw Muldoon's face, pale behind the water on his cheeks.", "Then he saw the animal.", "Not the whole animal. Not a museum shape. Not a miracle.", "One yellow eye. One wet black claw hooked over the crate floor. The lower jaw opening sideways in the dark.", "Jophery Brown tried to pull his hand back.", "Something inside the crate pulled harder.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Low angle beside the transfer crate wheel on wet concrete, a torn ID lanyard and one dropped glove caught in floodwater, rain streaking through hard floodlights, the crate shadow looming over the apron."}, "\"Shoot her!\" Muldoon shouted.", "No one shot.", "For half a second no one shot because Jophery Brown was still between the guns and the animal. For the next half second no one shot because the handler with the rifle could not get his footing. Then the tasers snapped white into the rain, and the raptor screamed, and Jophery Brown's body struck the rail with a sound softer than the crate had made.", "The men pulled him out.", "They pulled him out by the belt and the back of his shirt and the right boot. One boot stayed on. The other came off and lay under the crate wheel with the laces untied. His badge lanyard had snapped. The badge itself was gone.", "Jophery Brown was still making a sound.", "It was not a word. It was a wet, surprised sound, as if part of his body had not been informed that the rest of him had ended.", "The InGen doctor ran in from the utility truck. The doctor knelt. The doctor put both hands on Jophery Brown's side and said, \"Pressure.\"", "No one had a clean towel.", "One of the handlers gave him a yellow rain poncho.", "The poncho turned dark in two breaths.", "Past the doctor, past the rain, past the men breathing hard behind their face shields, the raptor crate shook once more against the gate.", "Every man stepped back.", "Robert Muldoon did not.", "Muldoon lifted his rifle, but the raptor had already withdrawn into the darkness of the crate, and there was only a sound in there now. A low sound. A thinking sound.", "The men around the pen looked at the crate.", "The doctor looked at Jophery Brown.", "The InGen operations supervisor looked at the clipboard in his hand.", "The clipboard had a plastic cover. The paper inside was still dry.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "An InGen operations clipboard under a plastic rain cover, emergency incident boxes half-filled, the word RESTRICTED AREA stamped across the top, floodlights blurred behind it."}, "At 11:42 p.m., Jophery Brown was loaded into the helicopter.", "At 11:51 p.m., the holding pen was marked secure.", "At 12:08 a.m., a man from Legal called the accident a restricted-area worker injury.", "At 12:19 a.m., someone from Operations asked whether the transfer yard could be cleaned before the investors arrived.", "No one answered at first.", "The rain did the answering. It pushed red water toward the service drain in slow threads. It carried straw, mud, torn cloth, and small pale curls of meat into the grate. Beneath the grate, under the concrete, the drain sump clicked once as something hard struck the metal screen below.", "No one heard it.", "Everyone was looking at the cage.", "By morning, the first memo had gone out.", "It did not say death.", "It did not say eaten.", "It did not say that the workers had pulled Jophery Brown out of the mouth of an animal and then stood around him in the rain with nothing clean enough to press against the hole.", "It said <i>incident residue</i>.", "It said <i>biohazard closure</i>.", "It said <i>temporary sanitation support required immediately</i>."], "epigraph": {"text": "They said the pen was secure. They said it every time.", "attribution": "— InGen transfer log, Oct 1993"}},
  2: {"n": 2, "title": "Chapter 2: The Barback", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A Puntarenas waterfront bar at dawn in 1993, wet wooden floor, stacked plastic stools, a single bare bulb, the Pacific gray through louvered shutters."}, "It had been three weeks since the rent went late when Eduardo Brenes walked into La Sirena del Pacífico.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} was hosing the floor. The bar had closed at four. The cook had left with a paper sack of leftover yuca and a cigarette behind his ear. Mateo Valverde stood in rubber boots and pushed gray water toward the drain with a yellow plastic broom. The broom had lost half its bristles the month before. He had not replaced it because the owner did not see floors.", "The shutters faced the Pacific. The Pacific was the color of an old radio.", "The door opened without a knock.", "Eduardo Brenes stood in the doorway with his hands in the pockets of a windbreaker that was newer than any windbreaker Eduardo Brenes had ever owned.", "\"<i>Maecillo</i>,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"You are early,\" Mateo Valverde said. \"Or late. I cannot tell anymore.\"", "\"Early.\"", "Eduardo Brenes stepped inside. He did not sit. He looked at the stools stacked on the bar, at the framed photograph of the 1986 soccer team, at the calendar from a marine paint company nobody in Puntarenas had bought paint from in two years. He looked at the floor last. The floor was the only thing that was wet.", "\"You came back a month ago,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"You did not come here for a month.\"", "\"No.\"", "Mateo Valverde leaned the broom against the bar. Eduardo Brenes had been thinner the last time Mateo Valverde saw him. His shoes today were new. His teeth were not new. He had filled out around the jaw without filling out anywhere else, the way a man fills out when he has eaten food he did not work for.", "\"Coffee?\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"No.\"", "\"Beer?\"", "\"No.\"", "\"Are you here as a friend or as something else?\"", "Eduardo Brenes did not answer. He sat on a crate by the door instead, the way men sat when they had already decided a conversation would not last long enough to deserve a chair.", "\"I have a job for you,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"What kind.\"", "\"Cleaning.\"", "\"Cleaning what.\"", "Eduardo Brenes looked at the floor.", "\"Cleaning a place,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"Two weeks. Maybe less. The pay is in dollars.\"", "\"How many dollars.\"", "Eduardo Brenes told him the number.", "Mateo Valverde did not say anything for a moment. The number was the rent for four months, plus the medicine for his mother for two months, plus a pair of shoes if he wanted shoes, which he did not.", "\"Where,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"You sign a paper before I can tell you where.\"", "\"That is not how a job works.\"", "\"That is how this job works.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A Costa Rican man in his late twenties leans on a battered bar counter at dawn, a yellow plastic broom across the wood, a stranger in a new windbreaker visible in the doorway."}, "Eduardo Brenes took a folded envelope from the new windbreaker. Inside was a single page in English with a red-and-black skeleton inside a shield at the top. Mateo Valverde could not read English well, but he could read enough to see that the page asked him not to talk, and then asked him again, and then asked him in a third way that took up the bottom half of the paper.", "\"They sent you with this,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"They sent me to find one person.\"", "\"And you chose me.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Why.\"", "\"Because you are quiet. Because your mother does not ask questions about money.\"", "Mateo Valverde set the page on the bar. He pushed it once with his finger to flatten the fold.", "\"What happened to the last person,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Eduardo Brenes looked at the door, at the shutters, at the bare bulb above the bar. He did not look at Mateo Valverde.", "\"He went home,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"Where is home for him.\"", "\"Not here.\"", "\"That is not an answer, Eduardo.\"", "\"It is the answer I have.\"", "Eduardo Brenes had been the boy who taught Mateo Valverde to clean fish. Eduardo Brenes had been the man who lent him forty colones the week his father was buried. Eduardo Brenes was sitting on a crate now in a windbreaker that smelled of a store, and the way he was saying <i>he went home</i> was not the way a friend tells another friend that a man had gone home.", "\"You did this work,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"I did the grounds. Not what you would do.\"", "\"Was it bad.\"", "Eduardo Brenes did not answer.", "\"Eduardo.\"", "\"I bought a boat,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"I did not buy a house with it, and I did not buy my mother a refrigerator with it. The boat is small and the boat is old. A boat is a thing you can leave in. Do you understand.\"", "Mateo Valverde understood and did not understand.", "\"Sign the paper,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"Or do not. Either way I do not come back here.\"", "Mateo Valverde signed the paper.", "He signed it with the pen behind the bar, the chewed-cap pen the cook used for the daily fish. Eduardo Brenes folded the paper back into the envelope, stood up from the crate, put a small slip with an address into Mateo Valverde's shirt pocket, and walked out without saying goodbye.", "The door swung once and stopped.", "Mateo Valverde finished hosing the floor.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A small concrete-floor room in a Puntarenas tenement, a cheap duffel bag half-packed on a single bed, a framed photograph of an older woman on the wall, gray morning light."}, "That night, Mateo Valverde packed.", "He packed the way a man packs when he does not know the weather. Two pairs of work pants. Three shirts. Rubber boots from the bar. A razor. A bar of soap. The small silver medal his mother had given him when he was eleven. A paperback novel about a sailor he had not finished in two years. A man on a boat needed something to hold.", "He left the camera. The paper he could not read all of had said no photography.", "He sat on the edge of the bed and looked at the photograph of his mother on the wall. It had been taken in Liberia in 1979. She was wearing a yellow dress. She was younger than Mateo Valverde was now.", "He turned off the light.", "In the morning, the slip in his shirt pocket said: <i>Hotel Rey de Oro, San José, sala de conferencias 4, 0900</i>."], "epigraph": {"text": "The hourly number was not a hospital number.", "attribution": "— Mateo Valverde, nine days later"}},
  3: {"n": 3, "title": "Chapter 3: Restricted Questions", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A small San José hotel conference room in 1993, brown carpet, a folding table, a glass of water sweating on a paper coaster, a stack of carbon-copy forms beside a black telephone."}, "The fourth conference room at Hotel Rey de Oro had no windows. It had a folding table, three plastic chairs, a beige telephone, and a woman who did not look up when {{Mateo Valverde}} came in. The plastic name tag at her collar said CARMEN VEGA.", "\"Sit,\" Carmen Vega said.", "Mateo Valverde sat.", "Carmen Vega turned a stack of forms toward him slowly, the way a person turned a tray of fruit toward a buyer at the central market, and placed a white plastic pen on top of it. The pen had the red-and-black skeleton logo.", "\"Identification.\"", "Mateo Valverde gave her his <i>cédula</i>. She looked at it, at his face, at the <i>cédula</i> again. She wrote the number across the top of the first form without asking how to spell his name.", "\"You will sign three documents,\" Carmen Vega said. \"Initial four places in the second. Print your name in block letters in the third. The signatures must match. The pen does not leave the room.\"", "\"May I read them,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"You may. The rate of pay began at the first paper in Puntarenas. Careful reading takes forty minutes.\"", "\"I would like to read carefully.\"", "\"Then read.\"", "The first document was a confidentiality agreement. It said he would not discuss the nature, location, personnel, animals, or operations of the facility. The Spanish translation used the words <i>materia biológica</i>, which Mateo Valverde had only ever read on a sign at a hospital.", "The second document was a medical disclosure. It asked for his blood type, his open wounds, his history with leptospirosis, rabies, or any zoonotic disease in the previous twelve months. <i>Zoonotic</i> was a word he had to ask about.", "\"Animal to person,\" Carmen Vega said. \"Or person to animal.\"", "\"What animals.\"", "\"The form does not require you to know.\"", "The third document was a restricted-access waiver. It told him not to enter live zones, not to photograph the facility, and not to discuss the nature, circumstances, or personnel of prior sanitation incidents. He read the third line twice.", "\"Prior sanitation incidents,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"What does that mean.\"", "Carmen Vega did not look up.", "\"It means exactly what it says.\"", "\"Was someone hurt.\"", "Carmen Vega put her pen down. She placed both hands flat on the legal pad. She looked at Mateo Valverde for the first time.", "\"An incident has been logged,\" Carmen Vega said. \"The incident has been addressed. The facility is in compliance. The facility requires a temporary contractor in sanitation services. You are that contractor if you sign. If you do not sign, you receive travel reimbursement to Puntarenas and you do not return to this hotel.\"", "\"Has someone died.\"", "\"I cannot answer that.\"", "\"Cannot or will not.\"", "\"They are the same answer in this room.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A logistics coordinator in a beige blouse stamps a carbon-copy form, a clipped name tag at her collar, a folded map of Costa Rica behind her, fluorescent ceiling light."}, "Mateo Valverde initialed four places: live zones, photography, prior incidents, and a line that said all biological waste encountered during the contract belonged to the company. He printed his name in block letters. He signed three times.", "Carmen Vega checked each signature against his <i>cédula</i> with a small plastic ruler. She did not say what she was checking for. She stamped each form with a black rubber stamp that said COMPLETO, the date, and a four-digit number that meant nothing to Mateo Valverde. She put the forms into a manila folder, and the folder into a metal box on the floor beside her chair. The metal box had a padlock.", "\"You will receive a copy of the confidentiality agreement,\" Carmen Vega said. \"You will not receive a copy of the medical disclosure. You will not receive a copy of the waiver.\"", "\"Why not.\"", "\"Because you have agreed not to retain documents from the facility.\"", "\"This is not the facility.\"", "\"The forms are facility documents. They are restricted.\"", "She slid a single carbon-copy page across the table. The signature at the bottom was a faint blue. She put the page into a plain brown folder and gave him the folder.", "\"You will not open this in public,\" Carmen Vega said.", "\"It is mine.\"", "\"It is yours. You will not open it in public.\"", "She slid one more page across the table.", "\"Travel voucher. Bus to Puntarenas. Tonight. Boat at zero five hundred from dock seven. Bring identification. Bring this folder. Do not bring anything you cannot lose.\"", "The voucher was for a single passenger. It had no return.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A 1993 Costa Rican cross-country bus at dusk, a tired man in a clean shirt by a window holding a brown manila folder closed with both hands, San José city lights smearing past."}, "At 16:08, Mateo Valverde left Hotel Rey de Oro.", "At 17:30, he boarded the bus to Puntarenas.", "The bus was full. It smelled of plastic seat covers and someone else's coffee. He sat by the window with the brown folder on his knees. The folder weighed exactly one carbon-copy page, but he held it the way a man holds a thing he has been told not to drop.", "He thought of Carmen Vega's hands flat on the legal pad. He thought of the metal box with the padlock. He thought of a stamp number that meant something to someone who was not on this bus.", "The folder stayed closed.", "He arrived in Puntarenas at 21:47.", "The boat was at 05:00."], "epigraph": {"text": "You lose that, you don't exist.", "attribution": "— Dale Haskins, contractor orientation"}},
  4: {"n": 4, "title": "Chapter 4: The Crossing", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Puntarenas dock seven before dawn in 1993, a steel supply boat with a red-and-black logo on the hull, wet bollards, a thermos beside a coil of rope, gray water."}, "The boat was called the <i>Anne B. II</i>. The name was painted on the stern in red letters touched up unevenly, the second N newer than the first. The hull was steel. The wheelhouse had a red-and-black skeleton inside a shield stenciled on the door. A man in a wet jacket checked {{Mateo Valverde}}'s <i>cédula</i> at the gangway. He checked the brown folder without opening it, holding it in two hands the way a baker holds bread, then gave it back.", "\"Below,\" the man in the wet jacket said.", "Below was a low cabin with four bench seats and a folding table and a coffee urn that did not look as if it had ever been emptied. Four other workers were already there.", "Two of them wore badges on lanyards. The badges were laminated and worn at the corners. The lanyards were faded. These two did not look up.", "The third was a man in a tan canvas jacket and a baseball cap with a fishing-supply company logo. He was American. He looked up as soon as Mateo Valverde came down the steps.", "\"Cliff Donegan,\" the American said. \"Maintenance. Texas. You?\"", "\"Mateo Valverde. <i>Saneamiento</i>.\"", "\"Sanitation. Got it. First time?\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Me too. Well, second. Did a week last year for these people. Different island. Coffee?\"", "\"Thank you, no.\"", "\"Suit yourself. Coffee on the island is worse anyway.\"", "The fourth worker was a woman. She sat at the far end of the bench with a small duffel bag between her feet. Her hair was pulled back tight under a kerchief and her hands were red at the knuckles in the way that the hands of people who washed dishes for a living were red at the knuckles.", "\"Paola Ruiz,\" she said quietly, when Mateo Valverde looked her way.", "\"Mateo Valverde.\"", "\"Cocina del personal.\"", "\"Sanitation.\"", "She looked at him a second longer than he expected. Then she looked at her duffel bag.", "The boat began to move.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "The interior cabin of a 1993 supply boat at dawn, four workers on bench seats with badges and duffel bags, a coffee urn under a yellow bulb, a porthole showing rain on gray water."}, "The rain started at the second hour. By the third the sea had what the captain called a <i>pequeño chop</i>, which Mateo Valverde understood to mean a chop that was not small. Cliff Donegan was sick into a metal bucket for forty minutes. The two badged workers did not get sick. They sat with their elbows on their knees and their hands folded, and they did not speak to each other except to ask for the salt.", "Mateo Valverde tried, in the way a careful man tries.", "\"You have done this trip before,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes,\" the older of the two said.", "\"You are returning.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"How many weeks.\"", "\"Two.\"", "\"And the work is what.\"", "The older man looked at his hands.", "\"The work is what they tell you the work is,\" the older man said.", "The younger of the two was a thin man with a deep crease between his eyebrows that had been put there by squinting in sun. He had not said anything since Mateo Valverde came aboard. He looked up now.", "\"You are the new one,\" the thin man said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Sanitation.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "The thin man looked at the older man. The older man did not look back. The thin man looked at the porthole.", "\"Jophery was good,\" the thin man said.", "The cabin was quiet enough after that to hear the bucket slide six inches when the boat heeled.", "\"Jophery,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Was good,\" the thin man said again.", "The words were not a name. They were a closed door.", "Mateo Valverde waited. He waited the way he waited at the bar when a customer was deciding whether to order another beer or to leave. He waited a full minute. The thin man did not say anything else. The older man did not say anything else. Cliff Donegan made a noise into the bucket that was not a word.", "Paola Ruiz, at the far end of the bench, watched all of this without moving her head.", "\"Was he the man before me,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "The older man stood up. He did not answer. He went up the cabin steps and stood under the lip of the wheelhouse roof where the rain could not reach him, and he stayed there until the island came into view.", "The thin man stayed in the cabin and looked at the porthole.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A misty silhouette of Isla Nublar's volcanic ridge through rain at midday, a steel supply boat low in the swell, yellow emergency lights along a concrete service dock ahead."}, "The island came up out of the rain in pieces. First the ridge, which was the color of an old roof. Then the trees, which were the color of trees. Then the cliffs, which were the wrong color, because the cliffs had a band of gray concrete along the bottom that no cliff in nature had ever had. The concrete was a sea wall. The sea wall ran for what looked to Mateo Valverde like half a kilometer. The sea wall had a service dock cut into the middle of it, and yellow emergency lights along the edge of the dock, and a single steel gantry crane that was not moving.", "There were no guests visible.", "There was no welcome sign.", "There was a sign that said SERVICE in English and <i>SERVICIO</i> in Spanish, and beside the sign there was a smaller sign that said NO UNAUTHORIZED ENTRY, in English only.", "The <i>Anne B. II</i> slid against the dock with a soft heavy thud.", "Three men in green rain jackets came out of a small concrete building. They wore the same red-and-black skeleton patch on their sleeves. Two of them were holding rifles. The third was holding a clipboard.", "The man with the clipboard checked names in the order they were on the list, not the order the workers came off the boat. He did not say good morning.", "\"Donegan.\"", "\"Yo.\"", "\"Valverde.\"", "\"Sí.\"", "He wrote a small mark next to each name. The two badged workers did not need their names called. They walked past him and went through a door in the concrete building without looking back.", "Mateo Valverde watched the door close behind them.", "The rain on the dock was warmer than the rain on the boat had been. The yellow lights on the edge of the dock gave the wet concrete a color that was not a color of weather, but a color of a place where something had been hosed off recently.", "\"Follow,\" the man with the clipboard said.", "They followed.", "Behind them, the <i>Anne B. II</i> was already being loaded with crates Mateo Valverde had not seen come up from below. The crates were taped, labeled, and quiet. The crane began to move. The boat would leave at 16:30.", "The boat would not be back for fourteen days."], "epigraph": {"text": "The confidentiality rules are not complicated. You don't talk about what you don't see.", "attribution": "— InGen NDA, Section 4, subsection (c)"}},
  5: {"n": 5, "title": "Chapter 5: The Canteen", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A 1993 InGen prefab barracks dining area near the service dock, a long folding table under a single fluorescent strip, gray rain on louvered windows, plastic trays stacked."}, "The prefab building sat on concrete blocks at the inland edge of the service dock. It was the color of a thing bought from a catalog. The roof was corrugated metal. The walls were corrugated metal painted the color of a building nobody wanted to look at. The door was a screen door inside a steel door, and both doors closed with springs that did not match.", "Inside there were two rooms. The first had bunks. The second had a folding table longer than the room was wide, plastic chairs on both sides, a coffee urn, a stack of metal trays, and a single fluorescent strip across the ceiling.", "The strip flickered. Not steadily. It flickered at the rhythm of a man who could not remember the next word.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} took a tray.", "The food on the tray was rice, black beans, a piece of fried plantain, a piece of chicken cooked twice, and a small plastic cup of bright yellow gelatin with a piece of canned pineapple suspended in it.", "He sat down across from Paola Ruiz.", "\"You may sit somewhere else,\" Paola Ruiz said.", "\"I would rather not.\"", "\"Then sit.\"", "She had already eaten half her rice. She ate quickly, not the way a hungry person ate, but the way a person ate when she had been told that someone else needed the table.", "\"How long have you been on the island,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Since the boat with you.\"", "\"That was four hours ago.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"It feels longer.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "The two badged workers from the boat were at the far end of the table. They were eating faster than Paola Ruiz. They did not speak. They did not look at each other. They held their forks the way men held tools they had used for too long, and they finished their plates before Mateo Valverde had taken three bites.", "The thin one stood up first. He carried his tray to the bin, scraped it, set the tray on the rack.", "Then he turned.", "He walked back the long way past the table, on Mateo Valverde's side, and as he passed he looked down at the green badge clipped to the front of Mateo Valverde's coveralls. He did not stop walking. He did not slow. He did not say anything. He looked at the badge for the time it took him to take three steps past the chair, and that was longer than a man looked at a thing he was not interested in.", "The screen door opened. The screen door closed.", "The older worker followed him out a few seconds later. The older worker did not look at the badge. The older worker did not look at Mateo Valverde at all.", "The two of them were gone.", "The fluorescent light flickered.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Two workers eating from metal trays at a long folding table, one in a green temporary badge, the other a tired food-service woman, a flickering ceiling light overhead, rain on the windows behind them."}, "\"Paola,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Why does he look at my badge like that.\"", "Paola Ruiz did not look up. She moved her fork through the rice in a small careful pattern. She moved a piece of plantain to one side of the tray. She moved it back.", "\"Paola.\"", "\"I do not know him.\"", "\"He is from this island. You are from this island now. What does the look mean.\"", "\"I do not know him,\" Paola Ruiz said again.", "\"You heard something.\"", "She looked up.", "She looked at him for the way a person looked at someone they were about to like or dislike for a long time, and they had not decided yet.", "\"I heard at the dock,\" Paola Ruiz said, \"while you were giving your <i>cédula</i>, that the badge is a sanitation slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"That is what I heard.\"", "\"And.\"", "\"And nothing.\"", "\"Paola.\"", "\"And nothing, Mateo Valverde. The man with the clipboard said sanitation slot, and one of the men with rifles said <i>the sanitation slot</i>, and the man with the rifle did not say anything else.\"", "\"He said <i>the</i> slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Not <i>a</i> slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "She started eating faster. She ate the rest of the rice in three forkfuls. She ate the chicken without cutting it. She drank the gelatin in one swallow. She stood up with her tray.", "\"I am sorry,\" Paola Ruiz said.", "\"For what.\"", "\"For sitting at this table for shorter than I would have.\"", "She carried her tray to the bin. She scraped the tray. She set the tray on the rack. She walked out of the dining room into the bunk room without looking back. The door between the two rooms closed with a soft swing of a spring that did not match its other spring.", "Mateo Valverde sat alone at the long folding table.", "The fluorescent light flickered.", "He ate the rest of his food slowly, because he did not want to stand up, and because he did not want to be the next person to walk out of the dining room and let the spring on the door make a sound that the room would remember.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A single Costa Rican worker sits alone at a long folding table under one fluorescent light, his green temporary badge bright against off-white coveralls, rain streaks on the louvered window behind him."}, "When he finished he carried his tray to the bin, scraped it, set it on the rack.", "He looked at his badge.", "The badge said his name. The badge said TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR. The badge said SANITATION / BIOHAZARD. The badge said VALID: FOURTEEN DAYS.", "The badge did not say <i>the slot</i>.", "He turned off the dining room light by habit. The fluorescent strip went dark. A second strip he had not noticed, in the corner above the bins, came on by itself, in a way that meant the building had decided when a room was occupied and when a room was not.", "He stood very still.", "The corner light flickered too.", "He went into the bunk room and lay down on the bunk farthest from the door. Sleep did not come for a long time. When it came, he heard the screen door close, and the steel door close behind it, in the order they had closed when the two men had left, and then he heard them close again, and he understood without understanding that the building had been built by people who wanted everything to close twice."], "epigraph": {"text": "The island looked wrong from the water.", "attribution": "— Cliff Donegan, maintenance, Texas"}},
  6: {"n": 6, "title": "Chapter 6: Two Briefings", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A bare concrete briefing room in 1993 InGen service quarters, folding chairs in three rows, a man in a dark green rain jacket at a metal lectern with a clipboard, fluorescent light overhead."}, "The briefing room had no windows. It had concrete walls, a concrete floor, three uneven ranks of folding chairs, a metal lectern bolted to the floor, and a sign over the lectern that said NO RECORDING in English and <i>NO GRABACIÓN</i> in Spanish.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} sat in the second row.", "There were eleven other contractors in the room. They wore coveralls in three colors: green for sanitation, gray for maintenance, tan for food service. There was nobody in white. White was for the laboratory, and the laboratory did not come to this briefing.", "At 06:00 exactly, {{Robert Muldoon}} came into the room. He carried a clipboard and set it on the lectern. He gave no name. He did not look up at the contractors. He turned the first page of the clipboard and read.", "\"No entry to live zones without a handler,\" Robert Muldoon said.", "He paused. He turned the page.", "\"No deviation from authorized routes.\"", "He paused. He turned the page.", "\"No photography. No personal cameras. No personal recorders. No drawings of the facility. No notes on personnel. No notes on animals.\"", "He paused.", "\"If you hear an alarm you move to the nearest green-striped wall and you stay there. You do not move until a handler with a working radio tells you to move. A handler without a working radio is not a handler at that moment. He is a man in the same room as you.\"", "The man two seats from Mateo Valverde shifted in his chair.", "\"If a door is red-tagged you do not open it. You do not open it if you have access. You do not open it if you have been told to clean it. You do not open it if a man is shouting on the other side of it. You do not open it if a manager who outranks me tells you to open it, because no manager who outranks me will tell you to open a red-tagged door.\"", "He paused for the third time.", "A contractor in gray coveralls in the back row raised a hand.", "Robert Muldoon looked up from the clipboard for the first time.", "\"What if we don't follow the rules,\" the contractor in gray said.", "The room did not move.", "Robert Muldoon looked at the contractor in gray for a beat. He looked at the clipboard for a beat. He looked at the contractor again.", "\"That's a question for your next employer,\" Robert Muldoon said.", "He turned the clipboard over and tucked it under his arm.", "He walked out of the briefing room.", "The contractor in gray did not raise his hand again.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A long beige service corridor in 1993 InGen back-of-house, yellow floor tape, a steel door with a black analog card reader, a worker in green coveralls and one in a white lab coat passing in opposite directions."}, "At 06:24, Mateo Valverde was sent to find a janitorial supply closet in corridor C-7. The wall map said it was a six-minute walk if a man did not get lost.", "He got lost at the second junction, where the corridor split into one with green floor tape and one with yellow, and the wall sign that should have told him which was which was missing. The screw holes in the cinderblock were fresh. He stood at the junction with his green badge in his hand and looked at the holes.", "A door behind him opened.", "A man in a white lab coat stepped out into the corridor. He was thin. He was Asian. He held a folder against his chest with one hand and a lidless coffee cup in the other. He moved the way a man moved when his next twenty minutes had already been promised to someone else.", "He stopped because Mateo Valverde was standing in front of the door reader on the other side of the corridor.", "The man in the white lab coat had a name tag. The name tag said HENRY WU, PH.D.", "Henry Wu looked at the green badge.", "\"Temporary sanitation,\" Henry Wu said.", "\"Yes,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Henry Wu glanced at the door reader. He glanced at the corridor behind Mateo Valverde. He took a small breath, in the way of a man who had been told earlier in the morning to spend less time on certain conversations.", "\"The {{raptors}}' metabolic waste has high pathogen load,\" Henry Wu said. \"Don't let it contact broken skin.\"", "He paused.", "\"For your sake, obviously. Not theirs.\"", "Henry Wu was already moving past him. He stepped past Mateo Valverde and held his own white identification card to the reader. The reader clicked green at once. The door opened. Henry Wu went through the door. The door closed with a soft hydraulic sigh, and the lock engaged, and the corridor was again the way it had been before the door had opened, except for one thing.", "The reader on Mateo Valverde's side of the corridor had also turned green.", "The reason for that was not clear to him.", "He looked at the green badge in his hand. He looked at the reader. The green light blinked once and then steadied. The blink was the kind of blink a reader gave when it had decided that a person was authorized.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A worker in green coveralls stands alone at a steel door with a beige analog card reader glowing green, a temporary badge in one hand, fluorescent corridor light reflecting on wet boots."}, "Mateo Valverde stood at the reader for what he later understood to have been forty seconds. He stood the way a man stood at the door of a church he was not from.", "The reader stayed green.", "Behind him, somebody hit a cart against a wall and swore in English.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the door.", "The door was a steel door. The door had a small wired-glass window at eye height. Through the window he could see a longer corridor, beige walls, a row of mop buckets, a hand truck, and at the far end of the corridor a second door with a red tag hanging from the handle.", "He looked at the red tag.", "He could not read what was on the red tag from this far away.", "He looked at the green light on the reader.", "He looked back at the door.", "He opened the door."], "epigraph": {"text": "He said the animals don't go near that building. He said it twice.", "attribution": "— Paola Ruiz, kitchen staff"}},
  7: {"n": 7, "title": "Chapter 7: Temporary Badge", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A back-office InGen contractor desk in 1993, wet boots on beige tile, cheap paperwork, a green temporary badge under a laminator, storm clouds visible through a small jalousie window."}, "It had been nine days since {{Jophery Brown}} died when {{Mateo Valverde}} signed the temporary contract.", "The contract was in English first and Spanish second. The English took up more space. The Spanish used smaller letters, and some of the words in the Spanish were not the words Mateo Valverde would have used if he had been explaining the same thing to his mother. <i>Riesgo biológico</i>. <i>Acceso limitado</i>. <i>Subcontratista temporal</i>. The paper made the work sound like the work at Hospital San Juan de Dios, except the hourly number was not a hospital number, and the company logo at the top was a red-and-black dinosaur skeleton inside a shield.", "Mateo Valverde had read the number twice.", "Then he signed.", "The man across the desk was Dale Haskins. Dale Haskins had a red face, a wet contractor cap, and a forearm that had missed two places with sunscreen. He smelled of coffee and old rain. He had not sat down since Mateo arrived. He leaned over the desk as if sitting would make the meeting too official.", "\"Two weeks,\" Dale Haskins said. \"Maybe less. Maybe more. Depends on whether the regular team clears.\"", "\"Regular team,\" Mateo said.", "\"Private animal-control contractors. Security-certified. Former military, most of them. They don't have anyone available this week who can travel under the confidentiality rules.\"", "Mateo looked at the second page of the contract. There were four places where he had initialed. One of them said he understood that all waste encountered on {{Isla Nublar}} belonged to InGen.", "\"I am not animal control,\" Mateo said.", "Dale Haskins laughed once.", "\"Nobody said you were. You clean. You bag. You don't open animal doors. You don't touch fences. You don't ask questions in front of guests. You see blood, you treat it like blood. You see tissue, you treat it like tissue. You see anything with teeth still attached, you call the handler.\"", "He slid a plastic badge across the desk.", "The badge was green. The photograph on it had been taken ten minutes earlier under fluorescent light, with Mateo's hair still wet from the boat. Under the photograph it said:", "MATEO VALVERDE TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR SANITATION / BIOHAZARD VALID: FOURTEEN DAYS", "\"Don't lose that,\" Dale Haskins said. \"You lose that, you don't exist.\"", "Mateo thought it was a joke.", "It was not a funny joke, but men like Dale Haskins made jokes by telling the truth without looking at it.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo Valverde, a tired Costa Rican temporary sanitation contractor in off-white InGen facilities coveralls, holding a green temporary badge beside a wet staff-only corridor, analog reader glowing green."}, "The first door opened.", "Mateo held the badge to the reader beside the contractor office. The reader was a square beige box with a red light and a green light and a speaker grille full of dust. The green light blinked. The lock clicked. Dale Haskins pointed with his chin.", "\"See? You're official.\"", "Behind the door was not the park from the brochure.", "Behind the door was a service corridor with beige walls, yellow floor tape, mop buckets, a hand truck, a row of rubber boots, and a laminated sign that said STAFF ONLY in English and Spanish. The air smelled of bleach, wet cardboard, and something sweet underneath, something the heat had spoiled.", "A man in a dark green rain jacket passed them carrying a rifle pointed at the floor. He glanced once at Mateo's badge.", "\"New temp?\" he said.", "\"Sanitation,\" Dale Haskins said.", "The man with the rifle looked at Mateo's hands.", "\"Keep him out of live zones.\"", "\"He's not stupid.\"", "\"Didn't ask that.\"", "The man with the rifle kept walking.", "Mateo watched him go. The rifle was not clean. There was rust-colored dirt in the seam near the sling mount. Not old dirt. Wet dirt.", "\"That is security?\" Mateo asked.", "\"Asset containment,\" Dale Haskins said.", "\"With rifles.\"", "\"With procedures.\"", "They walked.", "The corridor opened into a staff canteen. Men in boots sat at plastic tables eating from metal trays. Some wore InGen patches. Some wore contractor patches. Some wore no patches at all, only field shirts with the sleeves rolled tight over large forearms. They spoke in English, mostly. They used words Mateo knew from American movies and did not like hearing over lunch: perimeter, sector, extraction, hot, cold, clean, dirty.", "No one at the tables looked surprised to see another worker.", "No one looked pleased.", "Mateo stood with his lunch tray and understood, before anyone said it, that every seat had a rank.", "He took the chair nearest the trash bins.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "An InGen staff canteen behind the visitor areas, plastic tables, ex-military contractors in wet field gear, Mateo alone near trash bins with his temporary badge bright against dull coveralls."}, "That afternoon, {{Tomás Araya}} gave him the real orientation.", "Tomás Araya was the senior sanitation tech. He had worked construction camps, port cold storage, hotel kitchens, and one government clinic where the drains had backed up into surgery during the rainy season. He had a permanent badge, a mustache stained at the middle, and a flashlight wrapped in black tape.", "\"Haskins told you the rules,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Good. Forget half. Remember the half that keeps your fingers.\"", "Tomás walked him through the waste route with no brochure language. Meat prep. Animal laundry. Staff toilets. Dock corridor. Medical cold room. {{Raptor}} service washdown. Storm drain cutoff. Dirty gear side. Clean gear side. Locker room. Chemical cage.", "\"You see green tape on a door, it means someone fixed it.\"", "\"And yellow?\"", "\"It means someone wants to remember to fix it.\"", "\"And red?\"", "Tomás stopped at the end of the corridor. A steel door stood there with a red tag hanging from the handle.", "\"Red means a manager signed a paper saying it was fixed.\"", "Mateo looked at the door.", "The door looked closed.", "Behind it, something struck metal once. Not hard. Testing.", "Tomás stayed where he was.", "Mateo stayed where he was.", "The steel door stayed closed.", "Tomás said, \"Raptor service is tomorrow night.\"", "Mateo looked at his green badge.", "The plastic was still clean."]},
  8: {"n": 8, "title": "Chapter 8: The Places Guests Don't See", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "An original 1993 InGen service map spread on a wet utility cart, hand-marked waste routes, staff-only corridors, dock arrows, raptor service area circled in pencil."}, "By the fifth day, {{Mateo Valverde}} knew the park by smell.", "The visitor center smelled of new stone, cold air, and expensive varnish if a person came in through the front. Mateo had never come in through the front. From behind, the same building smelled of fryer oil, cardboard boxes, bleach water, and the warm sour breath of garbage compactors waiting for parts from the mainland.", "The dock corridor smelled of diesel.", "The medical cold room smelled of alcohol and plastic.", "The maintenance tunnel under the east service road smelled of wet concrete and old batteries.", "The {{raptor}} service bay smelled different every day.", "That was the first thing {{Tomás Araya}} taught him.", "“Do not get used to it,” Tomás said.", "They stood outside the bay with rubber aprons over their coveralls. Tomás had wrapped his sleeves twice with tape. Mateo had copied him.", "“You mean the smell?”", "“I mean anything. This place changes its habits and then expects you to have known.”", "The door reader blinked green when Tomás used his permanent badge. It blinked green when Mateo used his temporary badge. The second green light mattered to Mateo more than he wanted it to. He had begun to learn which men looked through him and which men looked at the badge first. The badge made some of them let him pass. The badge did not make him belong.", "Inside, the bay was empty of animals.", "That was what the orientation said.", "Empty meant no animal body was currently visible from the safe side of the reinforced line. Empty did not mean quiet. Empty did not mean clean. Empty did not mean the air was free of what had been there.", "Hose reels hung on one wall. Biohazard bags stood in a yellow bin. Straw and feed waste clung to the grated trench that ran along the floor. The concrete sloped toward a drain sump with a steel cover bolted down at four corners. One bolt was missing. Someone had circled the empty hole with yellow paint.", "“Red tag?” Mateo asked.", "“Yellow paint is cheaper,” Tomás said.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A wet concrete raptor waste service bay, yellow emergency lights, hose reels, grated trench drain, red biohazard bags, straw and meat waste caught in the grate."}, "The work was not complicated.", "First, rinse the outer floor. Second, collect straw. Third, scrape solids into the biohazard bin. Fourth, flush the trench. Fifth, record volume by bag count, not by weight, because the scale had been waiting on a replacement part for eleven days.", "Mateo did the work.", "The men with rifles did not watch him do it. They watched the doors, the mesh, the corners, the places a person looked if a thing might come through. Mateo watched the floor.", "The floor told him more than the men did.", "Three days earlier the animal had eaten beef. The hair in the waste was short and black and mixed with straw. The day after that, the waste had more feathers because someone had tried poultry enrichment. The day after that, the waste had not been cleaned properly because the inspection team had been moved through the visitor side and every spare person had been sent to polish glass.", "On the fifth day, there was cloth in the grate.", "Not much. A strip as long as two fingers, dark blue under the brown. Mateo caught it on the scraper and held it up.", "Tomás saw it.", "“Bag it,” Tomás said.", "“It is fabric.”", "“From uniforms?”", "Tomás turned the hose toward the trench.", "“Do you want to work here tomorrow?”", "Mateo looked at the fabric. He looked at Tomás. He bagged it.", "After that, Mateo began drawing his own map.", "Not the map for guests. Not the map with tour roads and fences and pretty icons of animals. Mateo drew the map that mattered to waste: where carts could turn, where a hose could reach, where a door needed a shoulder, where the floor dropped half an inch and filled with water when it rained.", "He used the backs of safety data sheets and a pencil stolen from the canteen. Tomás saw the map on the third night and laughed through his nose.", "“You think they don’t have maps?”", "“I think I do not have their maps.”", "Tomás stopped laughing.", "“Good answer.”", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Mateo marking a handmade staff-route map on the back of a chemical safety sheet, utility corridor pipes and analog warning signs behind him."}, "The park had two versions of every place.", "There was the kitchen where guests would see steaks and cakes and red tablecloths. Behind that kitchen was the prep room where a side of beef could arrive bleeding through the paper because the thaw schedule had been changed twice.", "There was the visitor center with the skeletons. Beneath it was the service level where the tour vehicles slept and where a lift door stuck open unless a person kicked the lower track.", "There was the raptor pen from the outside, all fear and steel.", "Behind it, there was the washdown bay, the gear hallway, the clean-change corridor, the locker room, the chemical cage, and the access-control closet where a beige terminal sat on a folding table with a sign taped to it:", "DO NOT POWER CYCLE WITHOUT AUTHORIZATION.", "Someone had written below it in black marker:", "THEN FIX IT.", "On the ninth day, Evelyn Park found Mateo reading the sign.", "She was small, wet-haired, and younger than the voice she used on the radio. Her glasses had rain spots on them. A pager hung from her belt beside a ring of keys and two badge blanks.", "“You need that room?” she asked.", "“Then don’t need it.”", "“The reader outside sticks.”", "“The reader outside is older than my little brother.”", "“It worked.”", "“It works when the server likes you.”", "Mateo looked at his badge.", "Evelyn Park followed the glance.", "“Don’t worry. Temps are in the live table. If your face is on that badge, the system knows you.”", "“And if the system does not know me?”", "Evelyn Park smiled, but not very much.", "“Then stand near someone important.”", "The pager on her belt chirped. She looked down. Her smile went away.", "“Storm meeting,” she said.", "“Bad enough they’re pretending it isn’t.”", "She went through the access-control door. The reader gave her a green light before the badge had fully touched the plastic.", "Mateo watched the door close.", "Behind him, past two more corridors and one locked gate, the raptor service bay waited for the next washdown."]},
  9: {"n": 9, "title": "Chapter 9: Five-Minute Closure", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Storm rain hammering a staff-only loading bay on Isla Nublar, evacuation carts and wet clipboards abandoned near yellow floor tape, Mateo in sanitation coveralls pushing a utility cart."}, "At 6:31 p.m., the last shuttle call came through the service speakers.", "The speaker above the {{raptor}} washdown bay had a crack across its plastic cover. {{Mateo Valverde}} had cleaned that crack with a toothbrush two nights earlier because Dale Haskins said the investors noticed dust in places investors had no business looking. The speaker made every announcement sound as if the person talking had a hand over his mouth.", "All nonessential staff report to east transport. Repeat, all nonessential staff report to east transport.", "{{Tomás Araya}} looked up from the drain trench.", "“That means us,” Mateo said.", "“That means them,” Tomás said.", "He pointed with his chin toward the corridor, where two security men in rain gear passed without slowing. One carried a rifle. The other carried a waterproof case with red tape around it. Neither looked into the washdown bay.", "Mateo had both gloves inside the trench. Straw, meat scraps, and disinfectant foam clung to his sleeves. The drain had backed up because the stormwater line outside was already taking more water than it wanted. Five minutes, Haskins had said. A five-minute closure. Tie the bags, flush the trench, secure the sump, get on the shuttle.", "It had been seventeen minutes.", "The raptors were still contained.", "Everyone said that as if it solved every other problem.", "Contained did not make the trench drain. Contained did not move the bags. Contained did not make the meat smell less sweet in the wet air. Contained did not make Mateo’s badge dry.", "Tomás pulled the last red bag from the bin and twisted the top.", "“Go,” he said.", "“We are not done.”", "“You are temporary. Temporary means go when the boat is leaving.”", "Tomás tied the bag. His old permanent badge swung against his apron. It was scratched almost white at the edges.", "“I have one more room.”", "Mateo did not like that answer.", "Tomás saw his face and shook his head.", "“Don’t make a speech. Take the cart to the clean side. Wash your boots. If Haskins asks, I sent you.”", "The speaker cracked again.", "East transport departing in twenty minutes.", "Mateo pulled his gloves from the trench.", "Something hard struck his knuckle.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo kneeling beside a raptor waste drain sump, hose water and disinfectant foam swirling around straw, meat scraps, and a half-hidden laminated badge."}, "At first he thought it was a bolt.", "The missing bolt from the sump cover had been annoying him all week. He had looked for it with the long grabber tool and found nothing but straw and a strip of blue cloth. If he found the bolt now, at least one small stupid thing would be complete before the island came apart.", "He pushed two fingers into the foam and pinched the hard edge.", "It was not a bolt.", "It was a badge.", "The plastic had gone cloudy. Brown matter filled the clip slot. The lanyard was gone except for one torn thread hardened into the laminate. Mateo wiped the face with the cleanest part of his glove and saw one eye first, then a nose, then a name printed in black under the InGen logo.", "BROWN, JOPHERY RAPTOR SERVICE / PERMANENT STAFF", "Mateo stopped breathing through his mouth.", "Tomás saw the badge in Mateo’s hand.", "For one second the older man did not move.", "Then Tomás crossed the bay faster than Mateo had ever seen him cross any room.", "“Bag it,” Tomás said.", "“This is his.”", "“It was in the drain.”", "The way Tomás said his name was worse than shouting.", "Mateo looked from the badge to the drain sump. The foam slid around the grate. Something pale and fibrous clung under the steel lip and then vanished as water pulled it down.", "“They said he was injured,” Mateo said.", "Tomás took a breath through his nose.", "“They say many things.”", "The speaker popped again.", "All remaining nonessential staff, report now. East transport holding for five minutes.", "Five minutes.", "The same lie in a different room.", "The wall phone rang.", "Tomás and Mateo both looked at it because the wall phone had not rung once in nine days.", "Tomás picked up. He listened. He said, “Yes.” He listened again. He looked at Mateo. “He found it.”", "The phone made a small tinny voice.", "Tomás said, “No. Not in a bag. It has a name.”", "The voice became sharper.", "Tomás closed his eyes.", "“Understood.”", "He hung up.", "“Haskins?” Mateo asked.", "“Haskins says secure it in the locker. Clean side. He will collect after evacuation.”", "“We should give it to someone.”", "“Everyone is someone right now.”", "Tomás took a clear evidence sleeve from the cabinet, the kind they used for broken sharps. He held it open. Mateo dropped the badge inside. The sleeve sealed with a small zip sound.", "It looked clean in the plastic.", "That made it worse.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Jophery Brown's old permanent InGen badge sealed in a clear evidence sleeve, grime caught in the clip, Mateo's wet glove holding it under yellow emergency light."}, "The route to the locker room was short.", "Dirty bay. Gear hooks. Boot wash. Clean-change hallway. Locker room. Staff corridor. Shuttle point.", "Mateo knew that route better than any guest knew the tour road. He had walked it carrying bags, mops, broken hoses, crates of disinfectant, and once a bucket with a dead chicken in it because the feed team had put the wrong label on the wrong bin.", "He could walk it in three minutes if no door stuck.", "The first door opened with Tomás’s badge.", "The second door opened with Mateo’s badge.", "Green light. Click. Green light. Click.", "His badge worked. His badge had always worked.", "Tomás stayed on the dirty side.", "“Go,” Tomás said.", "“You said that already.”", "“And you are still here.”", "Mateo put the evidence sleeve under his arm and stepped into the clean-change hallway. The door closed behind him. The hallway was narrow, tiled, and too bright. On the left were the dirty lockers. On the right were the clean lockers. At the far end was the staff corridor door, beyond which the shuttle point waited in rain.", "Mateo opened locker 18.", "{{Jophery Brown}}’s name was still taped inside.", "Not on the outside. InGen had removed the outside label. Inside, behind the hanging hook, a strip of tape remained with J. BROWN written in black marker. The letters were neat and square.", "Mateo put the sleeve on the locker shelf.", "The lights flickered once.", "The ventilation stopped.", "Somewhere beyond the wall, the park made a sound Mateo had never heard before.", "Not a roar.", "Not an alarm.", "A silence turning on."]},
  10: {"n": 10, "title": "Chapter 10: Jophery Brown", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A narrow clean-change locker hallway in 1993 InGen service infrastructure, fluorescent lights flickering, wet boot prints, one open locker with J. BROWN written on tape inside."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not move for six seconds.", "He knew because the clock above the clean lockers still worked. It had a red second hand that jumped instead of swept. The hand clicked from twelve to one, from one to two, from two to three. Six clicks before Mateo remembered the shuttle.", "Then he moved.", "He shut {{Jophery Brown}}'s locker. He wiped his gloves on his apron because the evidence sleeve had been clean and the rest of him was not. He crossed the clean-change hallway and put his badge to the staff corridor reader.", "The reader did nothing.", "Mateo lifted the badge away and tried again.", "The red light blinked.", "He had seen red before. Red when he tried Tomás's chemical cage by mistake. Red when he held the badge too low. Red when rainwater got between the plastic and the reader. Red was not disaster. Red was a request to do it correctly.", "Mateo wiped the badge on his coverall.", "He pressed it flat.", "Red.", "Behind him, the dirty-side door clicked.", "That door had been locked since he came in. It clicked now not like an opening door, but like a door checking itself.", "Mateo turned.", "The dirty-side reader showed no light at all.", "\"Tomás?\"", "No answer.", "He pressed the staff corridor intercom button.", "The speaker gave him three seconds of voices.", "<i>...vehicles are stopped...</i>", "<i>...not the {{raptor}} fences, I said...</i>", "<i>...east transport final...</i>", "Then a burst of static filled the hallway so loudly Mateo stepped back.", "The static cut off.", "The hallway became small.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Close-up of Mateo's green temporary contractor badge pressed to a beige analog InGen badge reader, red light reflected in a wet glove, dead wall phone hanging nearby."}, "Mateo tried the badge six more times.", "The seventh time the little beige display below the reader woke up. He had not known the reader had a display. A line of green letters dragged themselves across the black strip one by one.", "LOCAL SAFE MODE ACTIVE", "He did not understand the words at first.", "He understood safe.", "That was the wrong word.", "The display changed.", "NETWORK CREDENTIAL TABLE UNAVAILABLE", "Then:", "CREDENTIAL NOT FOUND", "Mateo looked at his own photograph in the plastic badge. The photograph looked tired and flat under the laminate. The badge said his name. The machine said it did not.", "\"No,\" Mateo said.", "It was not a word for anyone else.", "He tried the dirty-side door.", "Red.", "He tried the staff corridor door.", "Red.", "He tried the wall phone. The receiver was still there, bolted to a metal cord. It had no dial, only three square buttons: CONTROL, SECURITY, MEDICAL. He pressed CONTROL. Nothing. SECURITY. Nothing. MEDICAL gave him a click and then the sound of someone breathing.", "\"Hello?\"", "The breathing continued.", "\"This is sanitation. Clean-change hallway by raptor service. I am locked in.\"", "The breathing became voices in the distance, not one person, many people. A man said, \"Hold on to your butts,\" far away and half-buried in static.", "Then the line died.", "Mateo held the receiver until the dead tone began.", "He hung the receiver up.", "The clock clicked seven more seconds.", "The shuttle would not wait for a temporary worker in a clean-change hallway.", "He opened Jophery Brown's locker again.", "The evidence sleeve lay on the shelf.", "Jophery's badge looked up from inside the plastic.", "Mateo did not touch it.", "Not yet.", "He searched the locker first because searching was not stealing. Searching was work. Searching was procedure.", "There was an old towel. A cracked comb. Two green uniform shirts folded badly. A packet of aspirin. A photograph of a woman and a boy at a picnic table, the boy holding a paper cup with both hands. A laminated cleaning checklist with three boxes marked in blue pen.", "At the bottom, behind one boot, was a folded route sheet.", "Mateo opened it.", "It was not an official map. It was better.", "Jophery Brown had drawn the raptor service block by hand. Not pretty. Not to scale. Useful. Door numbers. Reader types. Drain access. Ceiling panels. Manual releases. One note written beside the clean-change hallway:", "OLD READER. HATES NEW CARDS.", "Mateo laughed once.", "It came out wrong.", "The clock clicked.", "Then the dirty-side door reader chirped.", "Mateo froze.", "No one had touched it.", "The display blinked:", "LOCAL SAFE MODE ACTIVE", "Then:", "BROWN, JOPHERY - SERVICE AUTHORIZED", "The door did not open.", "The reader chirped again, as if waiting.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Jophery Brown's old permanent badge on a locker shelf beside a handmade raptor service route map, fluorescent light flickering over the name."}, "Mateo put his hand on the evidence sleeve.", "He took it away.", "He wiped his glove on his apron, slow, because the apron was not clean and the glove was not clean and the slowness gave him something to do that was not the next thing.", "He looked at the photograph of the woman and the boy with the paper cup.", "He looked at the strip of tape with J. BROWN in black marker.", "He looked at his own green badge clipped to his coverall, the laminate fogged at the edge where his thumb had pressed it against the reader six times.", "The clock clicked.", "His right hand reached the sleeve again. The plastic was thin between his fingers. He could feel the shape of the badge inside, the clip slot, the broken edge of the lanyard hole. His thumbnail caught the seam.", "He stopped.", "Tomás had said bag it. Haskins had said secure it. Both men had said the same thing using different words. Both men had said it as if the badge belonged to a paper trail that someone else would walk down later.", "There was no later anymore. There was a hallway, and two red lights, and a clock with a jumping second hand.", "Jophery Brown was dead.", "The machine remembered Jophery Brown.", "Mateo Valverde was alive.", "The machine had forgotten him.", "His thumbnail found the seam again.", "He tore open the evidence sleeve.", "The plastic made a sound too loud for the hallway.", "He wiped Jophery's badge with the towel. He wiped the magnetic stripe until the dried matter came off in brown flakes. He held the old permanent badge to the staff corridor reader.", "Red.", "He held it again.", "Red.", "On the third try, the reader went dark.", "For one bad second Mateo thought he had broken the only thing in the room that still believed in anyone.", "Then the green light came on.", "The lock clicked.", "The display printed one line.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - STAFF ACCESS", "The staff corridor door opened two inches.", "Mateo did not go through immediately.", "He looked back at the locker.", "Jophery Brown's towel lay on the bench. The photograph had fallen face down. The route sheet was in Mateo's left hand. The old badge was in his right.", "The clock clicked again.", "Mateo stepped through the door.", "Behind him, the clean-change hallway lights went out."]},
  11: {"n": 11, "title": "Chapter 11: Profile Not Found", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A storm-lashed staff-only service corridor opening toward rain, Mateo running with a handmade route sheet and old permanent badge, exposed pipes and yellow emergency lights behind him."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} ran the wrong way first.", "That was what saved him from believing the park still made sense.", "The staff corridor outside the clean-change hallway should have turned left toward the shuttle point. Mateo knew this because he had pushed carts through it for nine days. Left, then the boot wash, then the contractor entrance, then the covered path to east transport. Three minutes if the floor was dry. Four if the floor was wet. Five if a manager stopped him to ask why the bags were not labeled with the new stickers.", "Mateo turned left.", "The fire door at the end of the corridor was closed.", "Not locked. Closed was normal. Closed meant push the bar and move. He hit the bar with both hands.", "The door did not move.", "He hit it again.", "Above the bar, a new red tag hung from the latch, swinging in the air from his impact.", "SECURITY DEGRADE AUTO-SEAL ACTIVE", "No one had mentioned auto-seal in orientation.", "No one mentioned many things.", "Mateo put {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge to the reader. The reader thought for three seconds and gave him a green light.", "The door still did not move.", "Green did not mean open.", "That was the next lesson.", "Behind him, down the corridor he had come from, a PA speaker popped and said half a sentence.", "<i>...East Dock vessel departing at nineteen hundred...</i>", "Then the speaker died.", "Mateo looked at the red tag. He looked at Jophery's route sheet. Jophery's handwriting beside the main corridor said:", "FIRE DOOR FAILS SHUT WHEN NETWORK DROPS.", "Under it, in smaller letters:", "USE LAUNDRY.", "Mateo turned around.", "He ran right.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A 1993 InGen corridor fire door with SECURITY DEGRADE AUTO-SEAL ACTIVE tag, green badge reader light useless beside a door that will not open."}, "The laundry route was not on the guest map.", "The laundry route was not on the contractor orientation map either. It ran behind the service toilets, past a linen chute, through a room where damp staff uniforms hung on a pipe rack, then into the back of the kitchen corridor and out toward the shuttle point from the wrong side.", "Mateo had hated that route because the carts caught on the threshold.", "Now he loved the threshold because no manager had thought to put an auto-seal door there.", "He crossed the uniform room with his shoulder against the wet hanging shirts. Someone's radio lay on a folding table. He grabbed it. The battery clip had tape on it. He pressed the side button.", "\"East transport, this is sanitation. Mateo Valverde, {{raptor}} service. I am in the laundry route. Do you copy?\"", "Static.", "\"East transport, this is sanitation.\"", "A voice answered, but not to him.", "<i>Rosa, get those last two pallets off the pier or leave them. We are not holding for cargo.</i>", "Mateo pressed the button again.", "\"Rosa. This is Mateo Valverde. Temporary contractor. I am still on site.\"", "Static.", "Then:", "<i>Say again?</i>", "\"I am still on site. Raptor service. Badge failure. I am coming to the shuttle point.\"", "The radio hissed.", "<i>Who authorized you to stay?</i>", "Mateo almost laughed. He did not have enough breath.", "\"No one.\"", "The answer came broken by rain.", "<i>Then move.</i>", "He moved.", "He reached the shuttle point at 6:58 p.m.", "The covered pad outside the contractor entrance was empty.", "Not nearly empty.", "Empty.", "A clipboard hung from a nail beside the door, the pages limp with rain. A plastic sign had blown sideways and now pointed toward a wall. Tire tracks ran through standing water and curved toward the dock road.", "Mateo ran into the rain.", "The storm took the heat from him in one breath.", "He followed the tire tracks because tire tracks were more honest than signs. Past the staff generator shed. Past the waste cage. Past the low concrete wall where two days earlier he had seen a guest vehicle roll by clean and empty on its test route. Past a security post with the door open and the chair overturned.", "The road bent.", "He saw the dock lights.", "For three seconds, he thought he had made it.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Storm-lashed East Dock service overlook at night, cargo pallets under tarps, floodlights blurred by rain, the evacuation boat's stern light pulling away while Mateo reaches a chain-link fence too late."}, {"type": "image", "src": "action-1.webp", "alt": "Storm-lashed East Dock service overlook at night, Mateo gripping a chain-link fence as the evacuation boat's stern light recedes into heavy rain, tarps snapping over cargo pallets and floodlights flaring through mist."}, "The boat's stern light moved behind the rain.", "It was small. That was the thing that hurt. Not dramatic. Not close enough to shout to. A small red light, sliding away from the pier while the dark water rose and fell between it and the island.", "Mateo reached the chain-link fence above the service road. His hands struck the metal. Jophery Brown's badge hit the fence and swung from his fingers.", "\"Hey!\"", "The storm took the word.", "\"Hey!\"", "The boat did not slow.", "Below him, on the dock, two figures in rain gear were pulling the last line. One looked back once. Mateo saw the pale oval of a face under a hood. Maybe Rosa. Maybe not. The figure lifted an arm, not in farewell, not in greeting. A signal to someone on the boat.", "Then the line dropped.", "The boat moved again.", "The red stern light blurred, broke in the rain, and became nothing.", "Mateo stayed at the fence until his hands hurt.", "Behind him, inside the service corridor, a badge reader chirped.", "He turned.", "There was no one by the door.", "The reader chirped again.", "Jophery Brown's name appeared on the little green display.", "WELCOME BACK."]},
  12: {"n": 12, "title": "Chapter 12: Dead Man's Access", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A rain-lashed East Dock service gate after the evacuation boat has gone, yellow work lights on wet concrete, an analog badge reader glowing beside chain-link fence."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} stayed at the fence until the boat light became the same color as the rain.", "Then he made himself count.", "One breath for the dock. One breath for the road. One breath for the stupid green letters on the reader behind him.", "WELCOME BACK, JOPHERY BROWN.", "Diesel hung under the service awning. The smell tried to convince him the boat would turn. It did not. The east water went black. Dock lines slapped the pilings. Behind the maintenance shed, sheet metal banged once and kept banging, a loose corner working itself free in the storm.", "Mateo put his own badge to the dock office reader.", "Red.", "He put Jophery's badge to the reader.", "Green.", "The lock opened with a clean little click.", "He hated the sound. It was too polite. It sounded as if the park had been waiting for the dead man and was pleased he had kept his appointment.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Inside a narrow dock office, fluorescent tube buzzing, a clipboard under a plastic cover labeled EAST TRANSPORT MANIFEST, water beading the window glass, a beige dot-matrix printer below the radio desk."}, "The dock office was a narrow room with a radio desk, two rain jackets, a corkboard, and a clipboard under a plastic cover. The clipboard said EAST TRANSPORT MANIFEST. Every name had a mark beside it. Security. Maintenance. Animal containment. Food service. At the bottom, under temporary contractors, three printed names carried three pencil checks.", "Mateo Valverde was not there.", "He checked twice because paper sometimes lied badly.", "This paper lied cleanly.", "He picked up the radio handset. \"East transport, this is Mateo Valverde. Sanitation. I missed the vessel.\"", "The radio clicked.", "\"East transport, do you copy?\"", "Rain hit the roof. The loose sheet metal kept answering from outside.", "A printer under the desk woke up.", "It was not a modern printer. Beige box. Fanfold paper. Black tractor holes. It made a dry insect noise and dragged one line into the world.", "ACCESS EVENT: BROWN, JOPHERY LOCATION: EAST DOCK OFFICE STATUS: ACTIVE", "Mateo tore the paper off.", "\"No,\" he said.", "The printer gave him another line.", "ACTIVE PERSONNEL COUNT UPDATED.", "He looked through the office window at the empty dock.", "The park had counted a dead man and still had no place to put Mateo.", "He searched the drawers. A flare kit with two flares missing. A plastic poncho. A half roll of tape. A grease pencil. A packet of crackers sealed in foil. He took everything except the drawer itself.", "The route sheet from Jophery's locker had a corner map of the dock service road. Jophery had drawn arrows around the main gate and written:", "IF DOCK CLOSED, BACK THROUGH PUMP HOUSE.", "Mateo did not want the pump house.", "The pump house was inland. Inland meant fences. Fences meant animals. Animals meant the men with rifles had not stayed where Mateo needed them.", "He went anyway.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Concrete ramp under a pump house door, two blue chemical drums strapped under a wet tarp, a service road badge reader glowing in the dark behind chain-link, rain sheeting from the awning."}, "The pump house door stood ten meters past the dock office, half hidden by two blue drums strapped under a tarp. Water ran down the little concrete ramp leading to it. Mateo tried his own badge first. He had to know.", "Red.", "Jophery's badge gave green.", "Inside, the air smelled of hot motors and old salt. Pumps thudded below the floor, moving water through pipes Mateo had never seen on a visitor map. A wall panel showed dock sump levels in red needles. Two needles sat in the yellow. One was buried in the red.", "On the far wall, a second reader blinked beside a door marked SERVICE ROAD B.", "Mateo crossed to it.", "The pump under his boots stopped.", "Not slowed. Not coughed.", "Stopped.", "Every pipe in the room clicked once as pressure changed.", "The reader by the service road went green before Mateo touched it.", "From the dark space beyond the door, something breathed through its nose."]},
  13: {"n": 13, "title": "Chapter 13: The Last Shuttle", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A worker crouched on a wet pump house roof in heavy rain, gravel under his palms, an abandoned yellow shuttle bus at an angle on a service road below, one headlight pointed at the trees."}, "The breath came from low down.", "Mateo did not move his feet. Moving feet made rubber squeak on wet concrete. He had learned that in the {{raptor}} bay. Everything loud began as something small a worker forgot to respect.", "The door had opened only a handspan. Through the gap he saw rain, black leaves, and a pale shape near the ramp. It was not a raptor. Too low. Too round through the shoulder. It sniffed again and pushed its nose against the bottom of the door.", "Mateo saw small teeth.", "Not small enough.", "He backed up one step. The pump room gave him a stupid gift. The stopped motor restarted. The floor jumped under him. The animal outside flinched away from the door.", "Mateo hit the close button.", "Nothing happened.", "Of course.", "He used the grease pencil from the dock office and marked the door with one word.", "NO.", "Then he took the maintenance ladder.", "The ladder went up to a roof hatch and out into rain so hard it seemed personal. Mateo crawled, dragged the hatch shut, and lay flat on the gravel roof while the small animal below worried at the door gap. He kept the flare kit under his chest. He kept Jophery’s badge in his fist.", "When he lifted his head, he saw the last shuttle.", "It sat on the service road fifty meters inland, angled across the yellow line with one headlight pointing at the trees and one at the sky. The driver’s door hung open. Its hazard lights blinked without rhythm, as if one bulb had to think before it remembered.", "Mateo climbed down the far side of the pump house and ran crouched along the concrete drainage lip.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Interior of an abandoned tour shuttle at night, the driver's door hanging open, a clipboard on the dashboard, the green-glow radio handset in a worker's hand, rainwater pooling on rubber floor mats."}, "The shuttle smelled of wet vinyl, diesel, and fear.", "No driver. No passengers.", "The key was still in the ignition.", "Mateo laughed once, because his body was stupid and thought that meant luck.", "He turned the key.", "The engine coughed, caught for two seconds, and died.", "He tried again.", "The engine clicked.", "The fuel gauge lay flat under E.", "Someone had left the shuttle with the lights on and the engine running until it had drunk itself empty. The clipboard beside the driver’s seat had a printed route. EAST DOCK - VISITOR CENTER - HELIPAD SUPPORT. Under it, in pencil:", "NOT FOR TEMP STAFF.", "Mateo stared at the words until rainwater from his hair dropped onto the ink and made the T in TEMP blur.", "The shuttle radio still had power.", "He pressed the handset. “Anyone on transport channel, this is sanitation. I have a disabled shuttle on east service road.”", "Static.", "Then a child’s voice, far away and thin.", "“Hello?”", "Mateo froze.", "He knew that voice was not talking to him. It came through the wrong channel, bent by water and failing repeaters. It was young. It tried not to sound young.", "“Hello? Lex, don’t touch–“", "A boy’s voice cut through, faster, higher.", "“It’s pulling, it’s pulling the cable–“", "The girl again. “Shut up, shut up, please.”", "Then a man’s voice. Far. One word, shouted, the rest cut.", "“–down–“", "Something heavy hit metal. Not gunshot. Not engine. Weight against a frame. The sound a body made against the side of something built to hold its shape. The radio carrier held the noise long enough for Mateo to count two of his own heartbeats inside it.", "A new sound came under it. An alarm. Two tones. The kind that meant a door was open that should not be.", "Mateo reached for the transmit button.", "His thumb stopped above the red plastic.", "If he answered, what name would the system send?", "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not exist.", "{{Jophery Brown}} was active at East Dock.", "The radio display blinked, searched, and found a label.", "CALLER ID: BROWN, J.", "His thumb went cold against the plastic. The girl was waiting on the other end with a brother who was four or five and a man who had stopped shouting. If he keyed the mic, a dead man’s name would arrive in their speaker. He did not know if a child could hold that on top of whatever was eating their roof.", "He did not know if he could.", "He took his thumb off the button.", "The girl’s voice came back. Closer. A strange clean closeness, the kind that meant a repeater had finally caught.", "“Is someone there?”", "His chest pulled in once, hard, without his permission. He set the handset down on the seat as if it might break.", "Outside the shuttle, something heavy stepped into the water behind him."]},
  14: {"n": 14, "title": "Chapter 14: Return to Sender", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Under a tour shuttle bench at night, a worker's hands gripping a wrench, a thick gray dinosaur tongue touching the steering wheel, foil cracker wrapper on the floor."}, "Mateo slid under the shuttle bench.", "It was not bravery. It was not a plan. It was the only place his body found before the step outside became two steps, then three, then the wet sound of something large smelling the open driver’s door.", "The bench frame pressed into his ribs. A wrench rolled against his knee. He caught it before it could hit the floor.", "The thing outside put its head into the shuttle.", "Mateo saw a gray tongue touch the steering wheel.", "Not the tyrannosaur. Not a {{raptor}}. Bigger than the small animal at the pump house, with a heavy snout and eyes set where a cow’s eyes might have been if cows had been built from bad decisions. It huffed once and took the crackers from the seat with the wrapper still on.", "Mateo held the wrench with both hands.", "The animal chewed foil.", "The radio said, “Hello?”", "The animal lifted its head.", "Mateo let go of the wrench and grabbed the radio cord. He pulled the handset under the bench and pressed the side button against his chest to muffle it.", "“Do not answer this channel,” he whispered. “Go quiet.”", "Static.", "The animal outside swallowed the crackers and left.", "Mateo stayed under the bench until his legs shook from staying still.", "When he crawled out, the radio display had changed.", "TRANSMISSION ROUTED BROWN, J. / SERVICE MAINTENANCE", "Below that:", "RETURN TO SENDER", "He took the shuttle’s maintenance clipboard and the dead radio handset. The handset had a screw-on plug. Anything with a screw-on plug could be useful if a person was desperate enough.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A weathered communications cabinet under a tin rain shelter beside a service road, three padlocks of different ages, the bottom one already broken, a worker prying it open with a wrench."}, "The nearest communications cabinet was marked on Jophery’s route sheet as COM-3. It sat under a tin rain shelter beside the service road, between two trees that had grown too close to the concrete. The cabinet had three locks. Jophery’s badge opened the top lock. The middle lock needed a key. The bottom lock had been broken before Mateo was hired.", "He opened it with the wrench.", "Inside were phone junctions, paper tags, dust turned to paste, and a laminated service ticket sealed in a plastic sleeve.", "{{Jophery Brown}} had signed the ticket.", "READER D-17 MISREPORTS USER ID AFTER LOCAL FALLBACK. POSSIBLE BACKUP TABLE CORRUPTION. REQUEST: DO NOT CLOSE UNTIL TESTED.", "At the bottom, in a different hand:", "CLOSED - NO ISSUE FOUND.", "Mateo read it.", "He read it again.", "Not because it was complicated.", "Because it was simple.", "Jophery had seen it. Before the storm. Before Nedry. Before Mateo ever signed a contract. The park had been practicing how to forget people and call the forgetting fixed.", "Mateo used the grease pencil to write on the inside of the cabinet door.", "MATEO VALVERDE ALIVE EAST SERVICE ROAD TEMP SANITATION", "He added the time from his watch.", "Then he tried the cabinet phone.", "The line clicked through three empty rooms and one busy signal. A woman finally answered.", "“Maintenance dispatch.”", "Mateo almost dropped the handset.", "“This is {{Mateo Valverde}}. Temporary contractor. I am still on the island.”", "Silence.", "“Say again?”", "“Mateo Valverde. Sanitation. I missed evacuation. The access system has erased my badge.”", "More silence. Paper moved near the receiver.", "“This ticket is already closed,” the woman said.", "“What ticket?”", "“D-17 user mismatch. Brown, Jophery. Closed no issue found.”", "“No. Listen to me. I am not–“", "The line cut to a tone.", "The cabinet printer stamped one new status onto the old ticket.", "COMPLETED."]},
  15: {"n": 15, "title": "Chapter 15: The Park Remembers the Dead", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A dim staff break room behind a maintenance office, a corkboard crowded with worker photos, a soda machine without power, plastic chairs around a Formica table, fluorescent tube flickering above."}, "The staff break room was behind the maintenance office, past a soda machine with no power and a door that opened for Jophery without asking Mateo anything.", "Mateo went in because his hands would not stop shaking.", "He told himself he was looking for batteries.", "That was mostly true.", "The break room had a microwave, six plastic chairs, a sink full of mugs, a board of safety notices, and a cork strip crowded with photographs. Men on boats. Women holding babies. A boy in a school uniform with two front teeth missing. A wedding picture folded at the corner. A Polaroid of {{Tomás Araya}} standing beside a service cart with both thumbs up, pretending the cart was a race car.", "Mateo took the Polaroid down and put it in his shirt pocket.", "Not for a reason he could name.", "{{Jophery Brown}} had three photographs.", "The first showed him in a baseball cap, holding a fish. The fish was small. Jophery was proud anyway. He held it the way a man holds something that took longer than it should have. Mateo had cleaned that kind of pride off the floor of every break room he had ever worked. Men brought fish too small to feed anyone. Other men teased them. Then everyone went back to work, fed.", "The second photograph was a kitchen table. A woman sat on the left. Two girls sat in front of her. The youngest girl had birthday cake on her chin, a clean white smear under her bottom lip, eyes already laughing at whoever had pointed the camera. The older girl held a plastic fork like she was about to make a point with it.", "Mateo looked at the cake on the youngest girl's chin until his throat hurt.", "He moved to the third.", "The third photograph was the {{raptor}} service awning. Four men in coveralls. Jophery on the left, taller than the others, one hand on a wire fence post. Someone had written along the white border, in a careless slant.", "FIVE MINUTES, BROWN SAID.", "Mateo did not laugh.", "He understood the joke.", "Jophery had said five minutes was enough time to get safe, in a place where five minutes was not enough time to get safe. The men around him had laughed when he was alive. Then he had been wrong by a margin no one wanted to measure. Now they kept the photograph because grief found a way to wear a uniform.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A Formica desk with a worker's open cubby below a corkboard, a folded complaint form, a clean pair of socks, two pay stubs, a worker's hand reading careful printed handwriting."}, "He searched Jophery's cubby below the corkboard. Batteries. A clean pair of socks. A pack of gum. Two pay stubs. A folded complaint form.", "The complaint form was dated six days before Jophery died.", "It said reader D-17 had opened for the wrong person during a drill. It said the fallback table was older than the live roster. It said temporary and transfer personnel were not being tested under degrade conditions. It said, in Jophery's careful print:", "IF THIS FAILS DURING A CONTAINMENT EVENT, SOMEONE WILL BE LOCKED WHERE THEY SHOULD NOT BE.", "Dale Haskins had signed the bottom.", "ACKNOWLEDGED.", "No action line. No repair line.", "Acknowledged was a word people used when they wanted a problem to die on paper.", "Mateo put the complaint form with the manifest and the printed access log. Evidence was too strong a word. Evidence belonged to people who could stand in a room and be believed.", "He had paper.", "Paper got wet.", "The emergency light over the door blinked twice and turned steady red.", "The PA came alive.", "A woman read the same line in English and Spanish. ALL PERSONNEL TO NEAREST SECURE ROOM. Her voice was prerecorded. The pause between languages was always the same length, even now.", "Mateo looked at the secure-room sign on the wall. A green arrow. A diagram of a room with one door and no windows.", "He took Jophery's route sheet out of his back pocket.", "Jophery had drawn the same room. Same shape. Same arrow. In the margin, in the same careful print as the complaint form:", "NO WINDOWS. ONE READER. BAD HINGE.", "One worker, talking to another worker. A man who had walked the corridors enough times to know which doors lied. A man who had written the bad-hinge note before the storm, before Nedry, before Mateo was on a manifest.", "If the reader chose Jophery, the door opened.", "If the reader chose Mateo, the door did not.", "If the reader chose nothing, the bad hinge stayed where it had always been.", "He put the sheet back in his pocket and went the other way.", "In the hallway, the access panel showed a list of recent entries.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - EAST DOCK OFFICE BROWN, JOPHERY - PUMP HOUSE BROWN, JOPHERY - SHUTTLE 4 BROWN, JOPHERY - COM-3 BROWN, JOPHERY - STAFF BREAK ROOM", "The cursor blinked.", "Then it added one more line.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - RAPTOR SERVICE ENTRY", "Mateo was not at raptor service."]},
  16: {"n": 16, "title": "Chapter 16: Rex Weather", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A flooded maintenance tunnel under a culvert, brown water rising over a worker's boots, fluorescent bulbs failing in groups, a length of chain with a metal clip drifting past in the current."}, "The safest route on Jophery's sheet ran toward the sound.", "Mateo did not know what made the sound. Not at first. The building did not shake like a movie building. It shifted in small dishonest ways. Dust came down from pipe clamps. Water rings trembled in a coffee cup on a maintenance desk. Somewhere above him, metal bent with a long groan and then stopped.", "The men in the {{raptor}} yard had talked about the tyrannosaur the way people talked about a storm.", "Keep your distance. Watch the fences. Don't assume because it is far away that it is not coming.", "Rex weather, one of them had said, and the others laughed because men laughed when a phrase was good enough to hide behind.", "Mateo understood it now.", "The tour road maintenance tunnel ran beneath a culvert and came up behind generator shed C. It was supposed to be dry except during seasonal service. It was not dry. Brown water moved against Mateo's ankles and carried leaves, insulation, and one length of chain with a metal clip at the end.", "The chain had hair caught in it.", "Goat hair.", "Mateo stepped over it and did not look up at the ceiling.", "Looking up would not help.", "He followed the tunnel by touch. The lights failed in groups. Three bulbs on, two bulbs dead, one bulb buzzing like a trapped fly. Jophery's route sheet said the tunnel door at the far end opened with permanent staff access during local safe mode.", "It did.", "Green.", "Green lied less underground. The doors were older. They expected less from people.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Inside a half-flooded generator shed at night, a wall cracked near the floor, a glimpse of a downed fence and a yellow tour vehicle through the gap, a maintenance vest with reflective stripes hanging on a hook."}, "Generator shed C was half flooded. The outside wall had cracked near the floor. Through the crack Mateo saw a section of fence lying flat in mud and rain. Beyond it, the tour road disappeared into trees. One of the yellow tour vehicles sat sideways across the lane with its roof crushed down at the back.", "The goat chain ended under it.", "Mateo found two dry road flares in a cabinet, a coil of rope, and a maintenance vest with reflective stripes. He put the vest on because he wanted to be seen by people and not seen by animals, and the island did not allow both wishes at once.", "The shed radio was mounted to the wall. He tried it because he hated himself if he did not try.", "\"This is {{Mateo Valverde}}. Generator shed C. I am alive.\"", "The radio answered with a man's breathing.", "Then: \"Identify.\"", "Mateo closed his eyes.", "\"Mateo Valverde. Temporary sanitation.\"", "\"That name is not on my board.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"Who are you with?\"", "\"No one.\"", "\"How did you access C shed?\"", "Mateo looked at Jophery's badge in his hand.", "\"Permanent staff badge.\"", "The man swore softly. \"Brown?\"", "\"No.\"", "\"Brown is dead.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Then who the hell is using his badge?\"", "Before Mateo could answer, the outside fence wire jumped.", "Not from electricity.", "From weight.", "Something moved on the tour road. He saw only one foot in the mud, three toes spreading under the rain, each claw pressing a black crescent into the service lane.", "The radio man said, \"Do not move.\"", "Mateo looked at the door behind him.", "The reader light went out."]},
  17: {"n": 17, "title": "Chapter 17: Utility Level B", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A service hatch in a concrete shed floor, two recessed bolts loosened with a wrench, hot air rising from below into a dim utility tunnel"}, "Mateo got out through the floor.", "That was not a thing the safety signs admitted a person could do. The safety signs preferred stairs, muster points, and calm walking. The shed floor had a service hatch with two recessed bolts and a warning about confined spaces. The bolts were not tight. Nothing on the island was tight if a worker had needed to open it often enough.", "He used the wrench from the shuttle.", "Above him, the animal on the tour road breathed against the cracked wall.", "Mateo took his time on the second bolt. Hurrying stripped bolts. Stripped bolts made noise. Noise made teeth.", "The hatch opened into hot air.", "He climbed down a ladder into Utility Level B and pulled the hatch after him with one hand. The dark below smelled of old batteries, mineral water, and the green-black odor of drains that had been asked to do too much.", "He stood at the bottom of the ladder and listened to the building.", "A pipe overhead ticked with hot water. Another beside it ran cold and silent. The cold one was dead. He put his palm to it and confirmed. Pump house upstream had cut out, or someone had closed a valve. The hot one was still on the boiler loop. Boilers ran on their own logic for a long time after the men left.", "A floor channel pulled water past his boot in a thin pulse. Something somewhere was still washing.", "The cable trays hummed. Not all of them. Two of three. He counted as he walked. Lighting circuit live. Communication trunk live. Auxiliary tray dead. The park was not dark yet. The park was choosing what to keep on.", "Mateo read the systems the way another man read a face.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A long concrete service corridor with overhead pipe runs, cable trays, and laminated instruction plates, one bare bulb every twenty feet"}, "Utility Level B was not a level.", "It was a mistake repeated under different buildings until someone gave it a name.", "Concrete corridors. Pipe runs. Cable trays. Floor channels. Little rooms with pumps, switches, and laminated instructions written for men who already knew what they were looking at. Mateo had cleaned hospitals older than this park. Hospitals hid their important work in back corridors too. Oxygen. Waste. Laundry. Bodies. The front of a place could lie only because the back kept working.", "He walked the spine for a hundred feet before he found the schematic.", "It was bolted to the wall under yellowed plastic. Someone had drawn over the original lines in red grease pencil. Someone else had drawn over the red lines in blue. The corrections went two layers deep before anyone gave up.", "SERVICE SPINE B VISITOR CENTER / KITCHEN / CONTROL SUPPORT / NORTH MAINTENANCE", "Visitor center.", "Mateo touched the word with two wet fingers.", "If any rescue remained, it would go there. If any radio still reached the mainland, it would be near control. If the children on the wrong channel were real, the visitor center was where a child would run when adults told them a building was safe.", "He copied the schematic onto the back of the transport manifest with the grease pencil. The lines came out fat and ugly. Good. Pretty maps were for guests.", "Halfway down the spine, the lights changed color.", "Not off.", "Blue.", "The blue lights marked animal quarantine support. Mateo knew that from Tomás, who had said blue meant do not bring guest laundry through unless you wanted to sign more paper than your grandchildren could read.", "A manual valve wheel stood beside a door marked AIR HANDLER B-4. Someone had tied a strip of blue cloth around the wheel.", "The same blue as the fabric from the {{raptor}} drain.", "Mateo stopped.", "The route sheet had a note near B-4:", "SHORTCUT IF DRY. NEVER IF WET.", "The floor was wet.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A badge reader beside a steel door marked AIR HANDLER B-4 glowing green over an open palm in a corridor lit by cold blue safety bulbs"}, "Behind him, somewhere up the ladder shaft, metal screamed as the service hatch tore open.", "Mateo put Jophery's badge to B-4.", "Red.", "He put his own temporary badge to it because panic made people stupid.", "The reader thought longer than the others.", "Then it turned green.", "For the first time since the locker hallway, {{Mateo Valverde}} got a green light.", "He stood with his hand still on the reader. The green washed across his palm and the back of his wrist and the cuff of his shirt. The park knew his face. Under his own name. The system that had ignored him for two days now welcomed him by his payroll number into a corridor with quarantine cloth on the valve wheel and water on the floor.", "A small laugh moved in his chest and stopped before it reached his teeth.", "Up the spine, something heavy dropped from the ladder shaft and landed on concrete.", "Mateo went through B-4."]},
  18: {"n": 18, "title": "Chapter 18: Kitchen Light", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Service-side visitor center kitchen with stainless prep counters, swinging double doors, a fallen pan rack, and emergency bulbs reflected in puddled water across the tile."}, "The door opened because a forgotten reader remembered him.", "Mateo stood with his hand on the badge. He watched the green light. He waited for it to change.", "It did not.", "AIR HANDLER B-4 was loud, hot, narrow. The floor was wet under the fan housings. Wet was wrong. Dry meant no condensation spill. Dry meant no stormwater backflow. Dry meant no animal washdown pushing the wrong direction through the service spine.", "The shortcut was wet.", "Mateo went through anyway.", "He had stopped believing in good routes. He had routes that existed.", "The air handler put him behind the kitchen. He knew it before the sign. The smell told him. Cold meat. Lemon cleaner. Fryer oil gone stale. Something sweet left too long under glass.", "The kitchen lights were on.", "That was wrong enough to make him crouch.", "A safe building did not need every light. A building pretending to be safe did.", "He opened the service panel and stepped into the back corridor behind the freezers. Stainless steel broke the emergency bulbs into stripes. A rack of clean pans had fallen across the floor. One pan rocked. Slow. Small. Nothing had touched it. The compressor under the floor kept kicking on and off.", "Mateo listened.", "No voices. No radio. No men pretending.", "He moved through the prep area with one hand on the counter. Flour stuck to the water on his sleeve. Of all the things the island had put on him, flour was the most normal.", "There were prints on the floor.", "Small shoes.", "Two sets.", "Running.", "Mateo looked at the prints. He looked at the swinging kitchen doors. He looked at Jophery's sheet. Service route first. Guest route last. The park killed workers in the spaces between.", "He did not follow them into the dining room.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Two sets of small muddy shoe prints crossing wet kitchen tile beside a fallen ladle and a streak of flour, lit by a single emergency bulb under stainless prep counters."}, "He found a chef's jacket and wrapped it around his left forearm. Not armor. Cloth. Cloth was better than skin.", "In dry storage he took canned pineapple, a box cutter, and a rolling cart. The cart had a bad left wheel that pulled. He took it anyway. Carts belonged to him more than guns did.", "The freezer alarm began to beep.", "One beep every two seconds. Door open.", "Mateo turned toward the freezer aisle.", "The walk-in stood open three inches. Cold fog rolled out at floor level. Something inside scraped once against metal shelving.", "He backed away.", "The cart wheel squealed.", "The scraping stopped.", "Mateo crouched and grabbed the wheel with one hand to kill it. The cart twisted under his grip. A can fell from the lower shelf and hit the tile.", "The freezer door moved.", "Not much.", "Just enough.", "In the polished metal of the opposite counter, he saw the reflection.", "A long head. Lifting in the cold."]},
  19: {"n": 19, "title": "Chapter 19: Not My Rescue", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A back-of-house visitor center corridor split between guest stairs rising on the right and a staff service door on the left, wet boot prints crossing in opposite directions under a single emergency bulb."}, "Mateo did not run toward the guest stairs.", "He hated that later.", "At the time, he saw three things. The freezer reflection. The service door two meters behind him. A white towel hanging off the cart handle. He pulled the towel loose, threw it at the freezer alarm panel, and hit the service door with his shoulder before the animal in the cold decided the beeping meant food.", "The guest stairs were on his right.", "Voices came from that direction.", "A girl. A boy. A man shouting one word Mateo could not make out.", "He had one second to turn.", "He stopped instead.", "He put his hand flat against the wall and listened.", "The wall was cold under his palm. The voices bent. He could not tell if they were moving up the stairs or coming down them. The stairwell threw the sound. Carpet on the guest side ate the footsteps. He had walked the service spine of this building. He had never walked the guest stairs. He did not know which landing the voices were on. He did not know whether the man with the one word was above the children or below them.", "He did not know his geometry in the wrong half of the building.", "His feet were on tile. The voices were on carpet. Between him and them was a wall he could not see through. A guest stair he did not know the turns of. A landing that might be empty by the time he climbed it.", "The service door behind him was already closing.", "Green did not mean open.", "Open did not mean enough time.", "Mateo moved.", "He did not move toward the stairs.", "The corridor beyond the kitchen ran past staff toilets and a janitor closet. Mateo stopped with his forehead against the painted block wall. He could still hear the freezer alarm through the door. Then the alarm cut off.", "Something hit the kitchen side of the door.", "He kept moving.", "He told himself the children had adults. The guest stairs led upward. His route led to radios. One more body in the kitchen would not make the children safer.", "All those things might have been true.", "They did not help.", "At the janitor closet, someone groaned.", "Mateo opened the door with the box cutter in his hand.", "Rosa was inside.", "He knew her voice first. The woman from the radio. East transport. Her hair was plastered against her face. One trouser leg was black with blood below the knee. She held a mop handle like a spear and almost put it through his chest before she saw him.", "\"You,\" she said.", "\"Me.\"", "\"You missed it.\"", "\"I noticed.\"", "Rosa gave one breath that was almost a laugh and bent forward until her forehead touched the mop handle.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Rosa braced inside a janitor closet with bleach jugs and a yellow bucket behind her, mop handle lowered, blood blackening her left trouser leg, while Mateo crouches with a chef's jacket in one hand."}, "She had stayed for a driver who never reached the dock. A gate stuck. A tire blew. The radio told her to shelter. The shelter door locked on the wrong side. Every part of her story had an instruction in it. Every instruction had failed by five minutes.", "Mateo wrapped her leg with the chef's jacket. He tied it above the knee. He tied it again below.", "\"Can you walk?\"", "\"Badly.\"", "\"Badly is a kind of walking.\"", "\"You sound like my father.\"", "\"I am sorry.\"", "They moved together down the service corridor. Rosa knew the visitor center better than Mateo knew it. Mateo knew the underside better than Rosa. Between them they had half a map and one working leg.", "At the end of the corridor, a stairwell sign pointed up to HELIPAD SUPPORT.", "Rosa saw it and touched his arm.", "\"If they come back, that is where.\"", "The stairwell door had a reader. No manual bar. Mateo put his temporary badge to it.", "Red.", "Jophery's badge.", "Green.", "The lock opened.", "Behind them, from the kitchen service door, came three soft taps.", "Not impacts.", "Claws, testing."]},
  20: {"n": 20, "title": "Chapter 20: Compy Work", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A trash sorting room behind the visitor center with red biohazard bags split open, white food bags torn at the seams, floor drain grates clogged with rind and gauze, small wet three-toed prints crossing the tile."}, "The little ones came through the trash room.", "Mateo heard them before he saw them. Not footsteps. Too light. Scratches. Plastic crackling. Wet snouts pushing into bags. The sound made the hair on his arms lift because it belonged to work, not monsters. Rats in hospital bins. Dogs behind markets. Animals that found what people threw away and made a living from it.", "Rosa leaned on the mop handle and whispered, \"What is that?\"", "\"Garbage.\"", "\"Garbage does not breathe.\"", "\"This garbage does.\"", "The helipad stairwell had taken them up one level and stopped at a smoke door with no power. No red. No green. No light. The manual handle had been removed for construction and not replaced. Someone had taped over the empty screw holes as if tape could become metal if a supervisor did not look closely.", "They had gone back down.", "Now the service route forced them through waste sorting.", "Mateo hated that the little animals made sense there.", "Food scraps in white bags. Meat trimmings in red bags. Fruit rinds. Disposable cups. A whole tray of dessert squares tipped into a bin because some guest event had ended faster than planned. The back of the park had set a table for scavengers.", "One climbed onto a bag and looked at him.", "Then Mateo saw the rest.", "Not one. A room full.", "Three on the long bin against the wall. Two more behind the cardboard bale. Heads moving in and out of torn plastic. A pair tugging at the same red bag from opposite ends. Bright eyes everywhere he turned the flashlight. Narrow heads. Small bodies. Plenty of them.", "Mateo read the room the way he read any other.", "The bin liners had not been changed. The drain grates had not been raked. The compactor had not been run. A red bag near the door had been open long enough that the meat inside had gone the color a sanitation worker did not want to think about. The smell was warm. Warm meant time. Time meant these animals had been eating in this room for hours, maybe longer. They were not lost. They were boarders.", "Pest-control problem. Not monster problem. Same thing in the end.", "\"Do not kick them,\" he said.", "\"I was not going to kick them.\"", "\"Everyone kicks small things when afraid.\"", "He opened a cabinet and found powdered disinfectant, a spray wand, and a broken face shield. He poured disinfectant into a mop bucket and added water until the room stank sharp enough to make Rosa cough. Then he pushed the bucket ahead of them with the rolling cart.", "The little animals backed away from the smell.", "Not far.", "Far enough.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Small scavenging dinosaurs pulling away from a yellow mop bucket of harsh disinfectant, white chemical mist rising, Mateo and Rosa edging past torn red biohazard bags toward a service door."}, "Halfway across the room, Rosa slipped.", "Mateo caught her before she hit the floor. The mop handle clattered away.", "Every little head turned.", "Mateo threw the disinfectant bucket.", "The bucket hit the floor between the bags and burst white chemical water across the tile. The animals scattered. One did not scatter fast enough. It screamed. Not loudly. Not like a movie animal. Like a kettle pushed off a stove.", "More answered from behind the bins.", "Rosa got her feet under her.", "\"Move,\" she said.", "They moved.", "At the far door, Mateo saw red smears crossing the threshold ahead of them. Human blood or animal blood. He could not tell. He could tell where it went. The smears led toward the service corridor they needed.", "Blood trails were maps too.", "The little animals knew how to read them."]},
  21: {"n": 21, "title": "Chapter 21: Quarantine Route", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A blue-lit raptor quarantine corridor outside double doors, cloudy plastic curtain strips visible through the glass, wet floor tape peeling, Jophery's route sheet held in a hand smeared with disinfectant."}, "The quarantine route did not start with a door.", "It started with a smell.", "Not rot. Not meat. Not disinfectant. Something medicinal under wet fur. Mateo knew it from hospital cages where dogs woke badly from surgery. He stopped before the blue double doors and put his hand flat against the wall.", "Cold vibration.", "Fans were running on the other side.", "Rosa stood behind him with one shoulder against a pipe. Her face had gone the color of paper that had been wet and dried wrong.", "\"Tell me this is not the only way,\" she said.", "Mateo looked at the route sheet.", "The clean exterior route was crossed out. The helipad stair had no handle. The guest corridor had children, {{raptors}}, or both. The kitchen was no longer a kitchen in any useful sense.", "\"It is not the only way.\"", "Rosa waited.", "\"It is the shortest bad way.\"", "Jophery had written one line beside the quarantine doors:", "NEVER ALONE HERE.", "Mateo showed her.", "\"Good,\" Rosa said. \"Then you are following instructions.\"", "Jophery's badge opened the first door. The room beyond was a changing vestibule. Hooks on the wall. Masks on the hooks. Yellow boots in a row. A shower head hung from the ceiling like a question. The second door had no reader. It had a wheel lock.", "Mateo turned it slowly.", "The wheel squealed.", "Everything behind the door stopped moving.", "That was worse than noise.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A quarantine changing vestibule with yellow rubber boots in a row, hanging respirator masks, a ceiling-mounted shower head, and a heavy wheel-lock door stenciled DO NOT PROP OPEN."}, "They entered between plastic curtain strips gone cloudy from scratches.", "The room was wider than it should have been. Mateo counted steps without thinking. Twelve to the far wall, maybe fourteen with Rosa's leg. Cages lined both sides. The ceiling was low enough that the fans seemed closer than they should. The light was blue-white and unkind. It made Rosa's bandage look black and Mateo's hands look like they belonged to a man already dead.", "The cages were not large. Transport cages. Medical cages. Each had a clipboard wired to the door.", "Mateo moved past them and read tags as he went.", "Most were blank.", "One had a species number he did not know.", "One was handwritten.", "BITES LATCHES.", "He stopped on that one.", "An animal that learned hardware was a different problem. He looked back at the wheel lock on the door behind them. He looked at the shower head in the vestibule. He understood now why the vestibule had a drain in the floor.", "They were supposed to hose off whatever made it out before it made it any further.", "The floor drain in the room ran backward.", "Black water pushed up through the grate in slow pulses. Mateo crouched.", "A feather floated up.", "Then a second feather, smaller, paler.", "Then a strip of gauze, white at one end, pink at the other.", "\"Keep your foot out of that,\" he said.", "Rosa made a sound through her teeth.", "The drain pulsed again.", "They kept moving.", "Halfway through the room, something tapped the inside of an empty cage.", "Mateo turned the flashlight.", "Nothing inside.", "Tap.", "The sound came again. Not from the cage.", "From the air vent above it.", "He raised the light.", "The grille was a standard ventilation cover. Four screws. Painted white. The kind he had taken off and put back a hundred times in service corridors.", "The screws were turning.", "One. Then the next. Slow. Even. A hand on the other side that knew what a Phillips head was for.", "Rosa said, \"Mateo.\"", "The sound stopped.", "Mateo did not move. Rosa did not move. The fans kept running. The drain pulsed once more. The blue-white light buzzed.", "Then the screws began again.", "That was worse."]},
  22: {"n": 22, "title": "Chapter 22: Counting Error", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A personnel accountability terminal in a dark service office, green text listing BROWN ACTIVE and VALVERDE DEPARTED while rain beats the window glass."}, "Mateo held the vent grille in place with the mop handle while Rosa turned the screws back in by hand.", "The thing in the vent pushed once.", "Rosa said, \"Do not let go.\"", "\"I had not planned to.\"", "The screws were wet. Her fingers were wet. The animal behind the metal found the gap at the corner and put one claw through. The claw hooked the air. It missed Mateo's sleeve by two fingers. It vanished when Rosa got the last screw to bite.", "They did not wait to see if it held.", "The quarantine route let out behind the personnel accountability office. That name was printed on the door in calm black letters. Inside were two desks, one dead computer, one living terminal. A wall board ran the length of the back wall.", "Magnetic names. Three columns.", "ON SITE.", "EVACUATED.", "UNACCOUNTED.", "Mateo read the board the way he had learned to read Jophery's route sheet. As data. He counted ON SITE first. Eleven magnets. Then EVACUATED. Forty-three. Then UNACCOUNTED.", "Twenty-two.", "The numbers did not match the column header above them. Someone had drawn a line under the first nine names in EVACUATED and written PRINTED CONFIRM. The thirty-four below had no line. Pencil marks beside some. Question marks beside others.", "Rosa stood at his shoulder. \"What are you doing?\"", "\"Counting.\"", "\"Why?\"", "\"Because the system is.\"", "He found {{Tomás Araya}} under UNACCOUNTED. Magnet, no pencil. Just the name pressed into the felt.", "He found Rosa under EVACUATED. Magnet, no line. Pencil mark beside her last name. The pencil mark was a check, then a question mark drawn over the check.", "He found himself.", "EVACUATED. Pencil. Crossed once. Someone had written BOAT in small letters next to the cross.", "He touched the mark.", "The pencil told him a thing the print could not. Whoever wrote BOAT had not been sure. Print meant confirmation. Pencil meant guess. They had guessed him onto the boat because guessing was easier than calling the dock.", "He looked for {{Jophery Brown}}.", "No magnet.", "No pencil.", "No dead column for men who had been eaten by a failure everyone signed.", "The living terminal blinked behind him.", "ACCOUNTABILITY RECONCILIATION IN PROGRESS.", "Mateo pressed the arrow key.", "PERMANENT STAFF ACTIVE: BROWN, JOPHERY. TEMPORARY CONTRACTORS REMAINING: 0. ACTION: CORRECT MISMATCH?", "No was not an option.", "Only ENTER.", "He did not press it.", "The terminal pressed itself after ten seconds.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A magnetic evacuation board shows Rosa marked evacuated, Tomás unaccounted, Mateo penciled as BOAT, and no place at all for Jophery Brown."}, "The printer began.", "CORRECTION APPLIED. VALVERDE, MATEO. DEPARTED EAST DOCK. BROWN, JOPHERY. ACTIVE SERVICE RESPONSE.", "Mateo tore the paper so hard it ripped through the line with his name.", "Rosa did not tell him to calm down. That made him trust her more.", "\"We can take the board,\" she said.", "\"What?\"", "\"The magnets. The paper. Your crossed-out name.\"", "\"For who?\"", "\"For whoever tries to say you were never here.\"", "He pulled his magnet off the felt. Then Rosa's. Then Tomás's. He folded the torn reconciliation page into the plastic sleeve with Jophery's complaint.", "The terminal chimed.", "NEW SERVICE RESPONSE ASSIGNED.", "{{RAPTOR}} SERVICE ENTRY D-17. BROWN, JOPHERY REPORT IMMEDIATELY.", "Mateo turned back to the wall.", "The space where Tomás Araya's magnet had been was empty felt.", "He stared at the empty square long enough for Rosa to say his name once.", "Then the magnet for Tomás Araya slid by itself across the board, from where it was no longer, and settled into a fourth column that had not been there a minute ago.", "LOCKED IN ZONE."]},
  23: {"n": 23, "title": "Chapter 23: Raptor Silence", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A silent staff corridor outside raptor service, wet floor reflecting yellow emergency strips, three doors cracked open and a black badge reader at the far end."}, "The {{raptor}} service corridor had gone quiet.", "Mateo had never heard it quiet before.", "Even empty, the place had made noises. Fans. Drains. Distant relays. Men coughing into radios. The raptors themselves, sometimes. A bark or a scrape from behind layers of steel and mesh. Workplaces had sounds. Sounds told you which machines still cared.", "Now there was only water.", "Drip from the ceiling.", "Runoff under the door.", "Rosa breathing through pain beside him.", "Mateo held Jophery's badge away from his chest so it would not tap the plastic sleeve with every breath. He had begun to hate that little sound. It announced him to machines. It announced a dead man to doors.", "D-17 stood at the end of the hall.", "The reader with the bad complaint.", "The reader Jophery had reported.", "The reader that might open to Tomás or to nothing a person should enter.", "\"We do this fast,\" Rosa whispered.", "\"Fast breaks things.\"", "\"Slow gets eaten.\"", "Both true.", "They moved.", "Mateo went first along the wall. He put his right shoulder against the tile. He kept his left hand on the badge sleeve to stop it knocking. He set each boot heel down before the toe so the heel would catch grit before the toe could slide. Old kitchen rule. Still worked.", "The first raptor door was open.", "Not wide. Not broken. Open three inches, held by the automatic latch as if someone had asked politely. Mateo shone the flashlight at the gap and stopped the beam at the seam. He did not put the beam through.", "Empty smell. Straw. Bleach. Something under bleach.", "He moved past it without looking inside.", "Rosa came behind him on the bad leg. She slid her shoulder along the tile and slid her boot a hand's width at a time. Her jaw was set on her own breath. She did not make the breath into a sound. She used the breath to time the steps.", "The second door was open too.", "So was the third.", "No alarms.", "No red lights.", "The fans inside the holding rooms were not running. That was how he knew. The raptors lived under blown air. The blown air had stopped. The blown air did not stop unless the room did not need it.", "Quiet had a shape now.", "It was every door that should have been closed.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Three raptor service doors stand open three inches each, yellow warning labels darkened by water, a badge reader at the corridor end reflecting a man's face."}, "At D-17, the reader screen was black.", "Mateo saw his own face in it. Wet hair. Split lip he did not remember getting. One eye wide enough to look foolish.", "Behind his reflection, a second shape lifted its head.", "He did not turn.", "Turning took time.", "He grabbed Rosa by the front of her shirt and shoved her into the wall recess beside the reader. The recess was a hand deep. It was meant for a fire extinguisher. The extinguisher was gone.", "The raptor struck the corridor where her body had been.", "The animal hit tile and corrected without slipping.", "That was the terrible part.", "Everything else slipped here. Men. Carts. Water. Mateo. The raptor's feet found the floor like it had read it better than he ever would.", "Mateo slapped Jophery's badge against D-17.", "Nothing.", "He slapped it again. The badge rang flat against the panel like a coin on a counter.", "The animal lowered its head.", "The reader chirped green.", "Not from Mateo's side.", "From the other side of the door."]},
  24: {"n": 24, "title": "Chapter 24: Full Reboot", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A raptor service reader flickering red to green during a full system reboot, Mateo's temporary badge held against the panel while Jophery's badge dangles from his other hand."}, "The door opened inward.", "Mateo fell through it because he had been leaning into the reader, expecting failure. Rosa fell after him. The {{raptor}}'s jaw closed on the mop handle instead of her leg. Wood cracked. Rosa let go.", "The door shut.", "For one second the raptor was on the other side and they were alive.", "Then every light in the room went white.", "Not emergency white. Full white. Office white. Visitor-center white. The white of systems pretending nothing bad had happened because electricity had returned and electricity made cowards confident.", "A chime sounded through the room.", "FULL SYSTEM REBOOT COMPLETE.", "The speaker voice was cheerful.", "Mateo hated it more than the alarms.", "Rosa lay on her side, panting. \"Tell me that helps.\"", "Mateo looked at the reader inside the room.", "Jophery's badge: red.", "His temporary badge: red.", "He tried Jophery's again.", "Red.", "The display read:", "INVALID - DECEASED EMPLOYEE.", "Mateo stared at it.", "Rosa said, \"They fixed it.\"", "\"No.\"", "\"What do you mean no?\"", "\"They fixed the dead man.\"", "He put his temporary badge flat to the reader. This time the display did not reject it. It searched. Long enough for the raptor outside to put one claw into the gap below the door and pull.", "The display changed.", "TEMP PROFILE CACHE FOUND.", "Mateo stopped breathing.", "VALID FOR LOCAL EXIT ONLY. VALVERDE, MATEO.", "Green.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A beige reader display reads TEMP PROFILE CACHE FOUND / VALVERDE, MATEO while a raptor claw scrapes the bottom seam of the door and curls metal up."}, "He hit the open button.", "The wrong door opened.", "Not the corridor door. A rear service hatch behind them. The system had given Mateo what he was allowed to have, not what he wanted. Local exit. One way. No choice.", "He dragged Rosa through the hatch as the raptor peeled metal at the corridor door.", "The hatch dropped them into a narrow records room behind raptor service. Metal shelves to the ceiling. Old forms. Dead monitors. Boxes stacked three deep along one wall, each labeled INCIDENT VIDEO - DO NOT DUPLICATE.", "Mateo's flashlight crossed one box at eye level. The label had a date eight years before opening. An animal designation in code. The word RESTRICTED stamped twice.", "He did not stop. He did not read past it. The beam moved on.", "One monitor woke when the reboot reached it.", "It showed a map.", "Two dots.", "VALVERDE, M. - LOCAL EXIT BROWN, J. - DECEASED", "The map sat on the screen.", "Mateo lowered Rosa onto a folded canvas drop cloth.", "Rosa pressed her hand under her bad knee and held it.", "Mateo found the room's only other exit, a service door with a manual lever, and put his weight against the lever to test the spring.", "The map zoomed.", "TRANSMITTING LOCATION TO CENTRAL SECURITY.", "For the first time all night, the park knew where Mateo was."]},
  25: {"n": 25, "title": "Chapter 25: After the Click", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A records room behind raptor service, shelves of incident tapes stacked three deep, an open service hatch above, and a monitor still transmitting a location dot."}, "After the click, the park woke in pieces.", "Not the right pieces.", "Fans came on in rooms with open doors. Locks cycled in empty halls. Freezer alarms reset. A phone rang under a desk no one could reach. Somewhere above {{raptor}} service, sprinklers began spraying water over concrete already wet enough to shine.", "The records-room monitor kept transmitting Mateo's location.", "Rosa smashed it with the tape box.", "The screen died.", "The little green transmit light on the CPU stayed on.", "\"That did not work,\" Mateo said.", "\"I noticed.\"", "He yanked the power cord. The green light died.", "From the corridor outside came the clean sound of a lock opening.", "Rosa looked at him.", "Mateo looked at the only other door.", "It had a manual latch and a deadbolt. The latch opened. The deadbolt did not. He used the wrench. The wrench slipped and took skin from his knuckles. He did not feel it until blood made the handle slick.", "\"Mateo.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"Mateo.\"", "\"I know.\"", "The deadbolt gave.", "They went through into a hall lined with staff lockers. Halfway down, a man sat against the wall with a radio in his lap.", "{{Tomás Araya}}.", "Mateo stopped so hard Rosa hit his back.", "Tomás opened one eye.", "\"Temporary,\" he said.", "Mateo dropped beside him.", "Tomás had a bite high on one arm and a bad cut across his side where something metal, not teeth, had opened him. He had tied a belt around the arm. The belt was wrong. Too low. Too loose. Work done one-handed in the dark.", "Mateo reached for the buckle to tighten it.", "Tomás pulled the arm back.", "Not violently. Just the firmness of a man who had decided.", "Mateo tried once more.", "\"Don't.\"", "Not loud. Just final.", "Mateo's hand stopped above the belt and did not come down.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Tomás Araya slumped beside green staff lockers with a radio in his lap, one arm belted wrong, emergency light catching wet tile and a fresh smear under his side."}, "\"Can you stand?\" Mateo asked.", "\"No.\"", "\"We can carry—\"", "\"No.\"", "Tomás looked at Rosa. \"You are supposed to be on a boat.\"", "\"Everyone keeps telling me.\"", "The corridor lock behind them clicked again.", "Tomás pushed his permanent badge into Mateo's hand.", "\"No.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"We have Jophery's.\"", "\"Dead now. System knows. Mine still has animal-service override.\"", "\"Then we take you.\"", "Tomás grabbed Mateo's sleeve with his good hand. His grip was weak. That made it worse.", "\"You take the living woman who can walk badly. You take the papers. You tell my sister I stayed mean to the end.\"", "\"No.\"", "Tomás smiled with one side of his mouth. \"Temporary means go when the boat is leaving.\"", "The door at the end of the locker hall opened.", "Tomás shoved his badge harder into Mateo's hand.", "Tomás's eyes did not close. They went to the locker across from him with the rust line under its number. He kept them there.", "Mateo took the badge because needing things was uglier than refusing them.", "They went."]},
  26: {"n": 26, "title": "Chapter 26: Kitchen Without Children", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "The Visitor Center kitchen after the attack, stainless counters streaked, a ladle under the stove line, freezer fog along the seam and raptor claw marks down a cabinet door."}, "The kitchen had no children in it.", "That was the first mercy.", "It had everything children left behind.", "Muddy prints on tile. A ladle under the stove line. A cabinet door hanging crooked. A pan dented where something had stepped on it. On the stainless counter, one small handprint in condensation, already fading because the freezer air had begun to warm.", "Mateo looked at the handprint too long.", "Rosa touched his arm. \"They got out.\"", "\"You know?\"", "\"No.\"", "It was an honest answer, which meant it helped.", "They had come back through the kitchen because Tomás's badge opened animal-service doors but not guest stairwells, and because the service spine to North Maintenance ran under the dish pit. Mateo did not think about Tomás after that sentence. He put the thought on a shelf. The shelf was wet. The shelf would break later.", "For now, kitchen.", "He read it like work.", "Freezer door scraped at bottom: opened hard, then blocked.", "Shelf knocked down but not collapsed: animal weight near edge, not full body.", "Food torn, not eaten: distraction.", "Water under dishwasher moving toward the wrong drain: storm line failing.", "The {{raptors}} had learned the room faster than the people who built the room.", "Rosa leaned on the prep counter. \"What are you doing?\"", "\"Trying not to step where they stepped.\"", "\"Why?\"", "\"Because they did not slip.\"", "The freezer bumped once.", "Both of them looked.", "The walk-in door was closed from the outside with a serving cart wedged under the handle. Frost melted down the seam.", "Rosa lifted the mop handle she had taken from Tomás's hall. \"Do we open it?\"", "Mateo listened.", "Another bump. Weak.", "Not claws.", "Knuckles.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A walk-in freezer door wedged shut by a stainless serving cart, frost melting down the seam, the handle vibrating where a fist taps from inside."}, "He moved the cart.", "A man fell out with the cold.", "Not a guest. Not security. Kitchen whites under a rain jacket. His lips were blue and one eyebrow had frozen stiff with blood. He blinked at Mateo and tried to say something, but his jaw shook too hard.", "Rosa and Mateo dragged him behind the counter.", "\"Name,\" Rosa said.", "\"Luis,\" the man managed.", "\"Can you walk?\"", "He laughed once, which became a cough. \"Everyone asks.\"", "Mateo wrapped him in two tablecloths and hated every second that used time.", "Luis clutched his sleeve.", "\"North Dock,\" he said.", "Mateo froze.", "\"What about it?\"", "\"Maintenance launch. Fuel locker. Haskins sent two men.\"", "\"When?\"", "\"Before the phones died.\"", "Rosa looked at Mateo.", "Mateo's hand on the tablecloth went slack for one second. He had stopped planning a route an hour ago. North Dock put a route back in his hand. Not a feeling. A tool. Something with edges he could grip wrong and still use.", "The freezer bumped again.", "Not from inside.", "From the door behind them, something copied the sound of a hand."]},
  27: {"n": 27, "title": "Chapter 27: North Dock Promise", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A hand-drawn route to North Dock spread on a kitchen counter beside Tomás's badge, Jophery's badge, and a cracked temporary badge with a melted corner."}, "North Dock was not on the guest map.", "It was on three bad maps and one good rumor.", "Jophery's route sheet showed a service road broken by a creek crossing. Tomás's badge opened animal-service gates along the first half. Luis knew the fuel locker code because kitchen deliveries used the north route when investors wanted the east dock to look clean. Rosa knew the radio phrase for a maintenance launch because she had signed boats out twice and been yelled at both times for writing too slowly.", "Between them, they had almost enough.", "Almost was a cruel word.", "Luis could walk if Mateo took most of his weight. Rosa could walk if she hated the floor enough. Mateo could walk because nobody had asked his body permission.", "They left the kitchen through the dish pit and came out under the visitor center loading dock. Dawn had not arrived. The night had thinned. Rain still fell. The big storm was moving off or saving strength. Mateo did not trust either possibility.", "The North Dock route began behind a gate marked MAINTENANCE ONLY.", "Tomás's badge opened it.", "Mateo did not thank the machine.", "The service road beyond was narrow, cut through wet green walls. Twice they had to stop and listen. Once, a branch moved against the wind. Once, nothing moved at all and that was enough to make them crouch behind a utility cart until Luis started shaking from cold.", "At the creek crossing, the road was gone.", "Not flooded.", "Gone.", "Water had eaten the edge and dropped half the concrete into the channel. On the other side, the road continued as if nothing had happened because roads were stupid that way.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A washed-out service road creek crossing, broken concrete hanging over brown floodwater, three pipes strapped under the gap as a maintenance crossing."}, "Mateo found the old pipe bridge under the crossing.", "It was not meant for people. It was three pipes strapped to steel brackets, wet with spray, running over brown water full of branches. Jophery had drawn it as a dotted line and written:", "IF YOU ARE SMALL AND STUPID.", "\"Good news,\" Mateo said.", "Rosa looked at the pipes. \"No.\"", "\"It is on the map.\"", "\"That is not an argument.\"", "Luis laughed, then coughed until he had to sit.", "Mateo tied one end of the rope to the bracket on the near side. He looped the other end around his waist and held the slack in his teeth.", "\"Luis goes first,\" he said.", "Rosa turned her head. \"He can barely stand.\"", "\"He weighs the least. He will not shift the brackets.\"", "Luis looked at the pipes. He did not say anything. He took the rope from Mateo's hand and started moving.", "He did not look down. He set one boot, then the next, knees bent the way kitchen men set crates onto wet tile. The pipes rolled a quarter inch under him. He kept going. Halfway across, his shoulders hitched once. He kept going. He reached the far bracket, sat down hard on concrete, and lifted one hand to show he was alive.", "Rosa breathed out through her teeth.", "\"My turn,\" she said.", "She did not give Mateo time to argue.", "Her bad leg went on second. That was the part she could not hide. Each step started with the good leg testing pipe, then the bad leg dragging up beside it, weight passing across slow. Her face went tight at the corners of the mouth. Lips pressed flat. Jaw set the way a person sets it before lifting something heavier than it should be.", "Her hands did not touch the rope.", "Her hands stayed on her own thighs.", "She walked her palms down her trousers in time with the bad leg, pressing against the muscle like she was telling it to keep going one more step. Press. Step. Press. Step. The pipes hissed under her boots. A branch hit the bracket downstream. She did not look at it.", "She reached the far side and sat next to Luis without making a sound.", "Mateo went last.", "Halfway across, the pipe bracket shifted. Not broke. Shifted. Enough to drop his left foot into open air and slam his knee against steel.", "He bit his hand so he would not shout.", "The rope went tight at his waist. Luis had it. Luis, who had not spoken in an hour, was on the bracket on the far side with both hands locked on the line and his weight thrown back against the steel.", "Mateo got his boot back onto the pipe. He crossed the rest in four bad steps.", "On the far side, a radio fixed to a weather box crackled.", "\"North Dock,\" Rosa whispered.", "Mateo opened the box and lifted the handset.", "\"North Dock. This is service party on route. Three survivors.\"", "Static.", "Then a man's voice, close enough to hurt.", "\"Say name.\""]},
  28: {"n": 28, "title": "Chapter 28: The Wrong Dead Man", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A weather-box radio under rain at the North Dock road end, handset in Mateo's hand, the small display asking SAY NAME while three survivors crouch below the pipe bridge."}, "Mateo knew the right answer.", "That was the problem.", "He looked at Rosa. She had one hand on the rope around Luis and one hand on the pipe rail. She heard the voice. She heard the question. She also saw the badges on Mateo's lanyard: green temporary plastic, Jophery's cloudy permanent card, Tomás's scratched animal-service override.", "Say name.", "Mateo pressed the handset.", "\"{{Mateo Valverde}}.\"", "Static.", "The man's voice came back flatter. \"No active Valverde on island manifest.\"", "\"The manifest is wrong.\"", "\"Identify by active credential.\"", "Mateo closed his eyes.", "Rosa said, \"Mateo.\"", "Not warning. Not permission. Just his name, so one human being had said it before the machine took it.", "He pressed the button again.", "\"{{Jophery Brown}}.\"", "The radio clicked into a different channel at once.", "\"Brown, you are listed deceased.\"", "\"Then your list is half right.\"", "Silence.", "Luis whispered, \"Jesus.\"", "The man on the radio said, \"How many with you?\"", "\"Three. One injured transport. One kitchen staff hypothermic. One temporary contractor.\"", "\"Temporary contractor does not show.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"North Dock launch has fuel for one crossing. Gate is locked under animal-service control. Approach lights are off. We can open for Brown.\"", "Mateo looked at Tomás's badge.", "\"Open for Brown,\" he said.", "The words tasted bad.", "The gate on the far side of the road clicked so loudly they heard it through the rain.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A North Dock access gate in the distance unlocking under a red animal-service light while jungle rain runs across the service road."}, "They moved faster after that because shame was also a kind of fuel.", "The road narrowed. The jungle pressed close. Once, Rosa stopped and pointed to mud where three-toed tracks crossed the road and vanished into ferns. The tracks were not huge. They did not need to be.", "At the final bend, they saw North Dock lights.", "Two of them.", "Low yellow bulbs over a fuel shed.", "Not enough light for rescue.", "Enough for bait.", "The launch sat in black water beside the dock, small, white, and real. A man in a poncho stood near it with a shotgun pointed at the ground. He raised the gun when he saw them.", "\"Brown?\"", "Mateo stepped forward.", "\"No.\"", "The man's face changed.", "Behind the fuel shed, the jungle answered in a voice Mateo had heard only once before: not a roar, not a scream, a low testing bark that made every dock light tremble.", "The man with the shotgun lifted the gun toward Mateo.", "\"You said Brown.\""]},
  29: {"n": 29, "title": "Chapter 29: Using the Park", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "North Dock maintenance yard at night, fuel shed, white launch, service gate, bait freezer, hose reel, and yellow bulbs in heavy rain."}, "Mateo stopped being polite to the park.", "That was the difference.", "Before North Dock, he had asked doors to open. He had asked radios to believe him. He had asked maps to be right and badges to mean what the plastic said. At North Dock, with a shotgun pointed at his chest and the jungle making {{raptor}} sounds behind the fuel shed, he stopped asking.", "He used what was there.", "The man with the shotgun was named Pike. He worked maintenance launch. He had been told to wait for Brown. He had not been told Brown was dead because InGen information moved like a drain full of hair: slowly, badly, and only after pressure built enough to flood the floor.", "\"Put the gun down,\" Rosa said.", "Pike did not.", "Mateo looked past him.", "Fuel shed. Hose reel. Bait freezer for dock scavenger control. Laundry cart with canvas sides. Gate reader. Manual winch. Emergency horn. All things workers used when nobody important watched.", "The raptor bark came again.", "Pike turned his head.", "Mateo moved.", "He did not hit Pike. He hit the emergency horn.", "The dock screamed.", "Every animal in the trees turned toward the sound. Pike fired into leaves. Rosa shoved Luis behind the bait freezer and put her own weight against the shotgun barrel, pushing it down toward the concrete with both hands. Mateo grabbed the fuel hose, opened the valve, and sprayed diesel across the concrete between the gate and the shed.", "\"Are you insane?\" Pike shouted.", "\"No.\"", "That was not fully true.", "Mateo threw one of the road flares.", "The diesel did not explode. Movies lied. It burned ugly and low, a dirty orange line that made heat shimmer over the wet concrete and put a smell in the air so strong even the rain could not flatten it.", "The raptor came to the edge of the light and stopped.", "Not afraid.", "Calculating.", "Pike looked at Mateo. Mateo was already moving. Pike's mouth opened, then closed. Something settled in his face the way a wrench settles into the right size nut. He did not say yes. He let the shotgun barrel come up off the concrete on his own and followed.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A dirty orange diesel fire line burning across wet North Dock concrete between a raptor silhouette at the tree edge and the white maintenance launch."}, "Mateo used Tomás's badge on the bait freezer.", "Green.", "He opened it and almost vomited from the smell. Old meat. Fish heads. Something labeled GOAT PARTS - DO NOT USE GUEST CART.", "He shoved the bait bin onto the laundry cart.", "\"Push,\" he told Pike.", "\"What?\"", "\"Push the cart.\"", "\"To where?\"", "Mateo pointed at the gate reader.", "Pike looked at the fire. Then at the raptor. Then at Mateo, who was temporary and no longer asking.", "They pushed.", "The bad wheel on the laundry cart screamed. The raptor's head followed the sound. Mateo slapped Jophery's badge against the gate reader.", "Red.", "INVALID - DECEASED EMPLOYEE.", "Luis came out from behind the freezer, dragging one boot, and called over the horn. \"Service gate. Tomás's card. The east post, not this one.\" He pointed his hand flat at the post, the way a kitchen man points across a counter to the right tray. He sat back down.", "Mateo moved his hand to the east reader and used Tomás's badge.", "Green.", "The gate opened.", "Mateo kicked the bait cart through. It rolled down the slight service slope, bad wheel screaming, meat smell pouring out behind it. The raptor crossed the fire line in one jump and went after the cart.", "The second raptor did not.", "It had come from the dock side.", "It stood between them and the launch.", "Mateo looked at his own cracked temporary badge.", "One local exit, the system had said.", "He pressed it to the launch access reader.", "The reader did not go red the polite way.", "The screen woke up. White text on black. Three words.", "TEMP CREDENTIAL EXPIRED.", "The park said his name one last time and said it with contempt.", "Mateo took the box cutter out of his pocket and began the seal."]},
  30: {"n": 30, "title": "Chapter 30: Left Behind", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Dawn at North Dock after the storm, a maintenance launch pulling from the pier, smoke rising over wet concrete, three badges scattered on the deck."}, "The launch access reader did not care that Mateo was alive.", "The screen still showed it.", "TEMP CREDENTIAL EXPIRED.", "He tried Tomás's badge.", "Red.", "Jophery's.", "Red.", "Three cards. Three little deaths.", "Pike shouted something from the dock. Rosa shouted back. Luis was coughing behind the fuel shed. The second {{raptor}} stood between the people and the boat with its head low and its tail held still. The fire made orange lines along its wet back.", "Mateo looked at the reader.", "Not the light.", "The screws.", "Four screws. Two rusted. One missing. One replaced with the wrong size.", "He laughed then, one short ugly sound, because of course.", "The park had not been built by miracles. It had been built by people who lost screws and covered the hole with tape. It had been maintained by men like Jophery and Tomás, who wrote warnings no one read. It could be opened the same way.", "He used the box cutter on the reader seal and the wrench on the wrong screw. The panel came loose enough to show wires. Red, black, yellow, green. He had seen the same colors in the hospital laundry lift. He touched red to green.", "The launch gate opened.", "Pike fired once. The raptor snapped sideways, not hit, only annoyed. Rosa threw the mop handle. It struck the fuel shed wall. The animal turned toward that smaller insult.", "\"Now,\" Mateo said.", "Everyone moved.", "Luis fell into the boat more than climbed. Rosa followed. Pike jumped down and started the engine with shaking hands. Mateo stayed at the reader with the wires pinched together until the gate finished its slow travel.", "The raptor saw him.", "For one second Mateo saw himself in its eye: wet, small, temporary, holding two wires because the official way had failed.", "Then the launch engine caught.", "Rosa reached for him.", "Mateo let go of the wires and ran.", "He made three steps before the raptor crossed the dock.", "Not enough steps.", "Rosa screamed his name. That was the important part. Not the pain in his shoulder, not the wood under his back, not Pike pulling the launch away because Rosa would have jumped back onto the dock if the boat stayed close enough to let her.", "His name.", "Mateo.", "The boat moved into gray water.", "The raptor dragged him once, then let go when the emergency horn cut through the dock again.", "Not the dock horn.", "Something larger.", "Aircraft.", "Mateo rolled onto his side. The dock boards were hot under his cheek from the diesel fire. Above the black line of jungle, three helicopters came in low over the island. Behind them, farther out, fixed-wing aircraft held a steady line over the water.", "The old shorthand opened in his mouth and closed again.", "Rex weather was something you could run from. There was no name for what was coming next.", "For one clean second, Mateo thought rescue had finally learned his route.", "He pushed himself up with one hand. The other arm did not answer. He lifted Jophery's badge instead. It had fallen near his knee, cloudy plastic catching dawn light.", "\"Here,\" he said, though no one could hear. \"Here.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo on the burning dock lifting Jophery's badge toward approaching aircraft, mistaking the firebombing run for rescue."}, "The first canister fell beyond the visitor center.", "It did not look like a bomb from far away. It looked like cargo. A gray shape released from a machine and turning slowly, almost gently, as it dropped through the wet air.", "Then the trees became fire.", "Not fire like the diesel line. Not orange along the ground. This fire opened upward. It filled the jungle in one breath, a sheet of white and yellow that turned rain into steam before the rain touched it.", "The second canister fell closer.", "Mateo understood then.", "Not all at once. His mind tried to keep the rescue shape for another second. Helicopters meant people coming down. Aircraft meant help. Uniforms meant someone with a board, asking names. A country did not burn its own island while a worker still held up a badge.", "Except the board said he had left.", "Except the system had corrected the mismatch.", "Except {{Mateo Valverde}} was already safely departed on paper.", "The radio on the dock crackled through static.", "\"...all personnel clear...\"", "The third canister struck near the fuel shed.", "The air hit him before the fire did. It knocked him backward against the open launch gate and filled his mouth with hot metal. The plastic sleeve of papers burst open. Manifest, complaint, reconciliation page, Tomás's Polaroid, all of it lifted around him for one bright second like the park had decided to snow paper before it burned.", "Mateo saw Jophery's complaint catch fire at the corner.", "He saw his own temporary badge melt inward, photograph bending, name warping but not gone yet.", "He pressed the two badges together in his good hand.", "One dead man the system remembered.", "One living man the system had not.", "He looked at Jophery's badge. He looked at the water under the dock. He looked at the aircraft. The turn would have continued past the aircraft, across the line of jungle, back toward the visitor center and the kitchen and the road. His shoulders started the motion. They did not finish it. He was facing the water again before he knew he had stopped.", "The fourth canister fell.", "This time he did not mistake it for rescue."]}
};
